aGeneral Index %0a%0a%0a%0a469 %0a%0a%0a%0aNATURAL HISTORY OF PLINY. %0a%0a%0a%0aBOOK XXXII. 1 %0a%0aREMEDIES DERIVED FROM AQUATIC ANIMALS. %0a%0aCHAP. 1. (1.) — THE POWER OF NATURE AS MANIFESTED IN ANTI- %0aPATHIES. THE ECHENE1S : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aFollowing the proper order of things, we have now arrived %0aat the culminating point of the wonders manifested to us by %0athe operations of Nature. And even at the very outset, we %0afind spontaneously presented to us an incomparable illustration %0aof her mysterious powers : so much so, in fact, that beyond it %0awe feel ourselves bound to forbear extending our enquiries, %0athere being nothing to be found either equal or analogous to an %0aelement in which Nature quite triumphs over herself, and that, %0atoo, in such numberless ways. For what is there more unruly %0athan the sea, with its winds, its tornadoes, and its tempests ? %0aAnd yet in what department of her works has Nature been %0amore seconded by the ingenuity of man, than in this, by his %0ainventions of sails and of oars ? In addition to this, we are %0astruck with the ineffable might displayed by the Ocean's tides, %0a%0a1 It is in the last six Books of Pliny, and those only, we regret to say, %0athat we are enabled to avail ourselves of the new readings of the Bamberg %0aMS., which has been so admirably collated by M. Ian. In a vast number %0aof passages previously looked upon as hopelessly corrupt, or else not at all %0asuspected of being in a mutilated state, this MS. supplies words and clauses, %0athe existence of which in the original was hitherto unknown ; indeed by its %0aaid the indefatigable Sillig has been enabled, if we may be allowed tbe %0aterm, almost to rewrite tbe last six Books of Pliny. From a perusal of %0athese new readings, as Dr. Smith has justly remarked, we have reason to %0ainfer " that the text of the earlier Books is still in a very defective state, %0aand that much of the obscurity of Pliny may be traced to this cause." %0a%0aVOL. "VI. B %0a%0a%0a%0a2 %0a%0a%0a%0aflint's natural history. [Book XXXII. %0a%0a%0a%0aas they constantly ebb and flow, and so regulate the currents %0aof the sea as though they were the waters of one vast river. %0a%0aAnd yet all these forces, though acting in unison, and impel- %0aling in the same direction, a single fish, and that of a very %0adiminutive size — the fish known as the " echene'is" 2 — pos- %0asesses the power of counteracting. Winds may blow and %0astorms may rage, and yet the echene'is controls their fury, %0arestrains their mighty force, and bids ships stand still in their %0acareer ; a result which no cables, no anchors, from their pon- %0aderousness quite incapable of being weighed, could ever have %0aproduced ! A fish bridles the impetuous violence of the deep, %0aand subdues the frantic rage of the universe — and all this by %0ano effort of its own, no act of resistance on its part, no act at %0aall, in fact, but that of adhering to the bark ! Trifling as this %0aobject would appear, it suffices to counteract all these forces %0acombined, and to forbid the ship to pass onward in its way ! %0aFleets, armed for war, pile up towers and bulwarks on their %0adecks, in order that, upon the deep even, men may fight from %0abehind ramparts as it were. But alas for human vanity ! — %0awhen their prows, beaked as they are with brass and with %0airon, 3 and armed for the onset, can thus be arrested and %0arivetted to the spot by a little fish, no more than some half %0afoot in length ! %0a%0aAt the battle of Actium, it is said, a fish of this kind stopped %0athe praetorian ship 4 of Antonius in its course, at the moment that %0ahe was hastening from ship to ship to encourage and exhort his %0amen, and so compelled him to leave it and go on board another. %0aHence it was, that the fleet of Caesar gained the advantage 5 in %0athe onset, and charged with a redoubled impetuosity. In our %0aown time, too, one of these fish arrested the ship of the Em- %0aperor 6 Caius in its course, when he was returning from Astura %0ato Antium : 7 and thus, as the result proved, did an insignificant %0afish give presage of great events ; for no sooner had the em- %0aperor returned to Rome than he was pierced by the weapons of %0ahis own soldiers. Nor did this sudden stoppage of the ship %0a%0a2 The Echeneis remora of Linnaeus. See B. ix. c. 41. %0a%0a3 He alludes to the " rostra," or metal beaks, with which the prows of %0athe ships of war were furnished. %0a%0a4 An absurd tradition, no doubt, invented, probably, to palliate the dis- %0agrace of his defeat. %0a%0a5 From the delay caused by the stoppage of the praetorian ship. %0a%0a« Caligula. 1 For Astura and Antium, see B. iii. c. 9. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 1.] %0a%0a%0a%0aTHE ECHENE18. %0a%0a%0a%0a3 %0a%0a%0a%0along remain a mystery, the cause being perceived upon finding %0athat, out of the whole fleet, the emperor's five-banked galley %0awas the only one that was making no way. The moment this %0awas discovered, some of the sailors plunged into the sea, and, %0aon making search about the ship's sides, they found an %0aechene'is adhering to the rudder. Upon its being shown to %0athe emperor, he strongly expressed his indignation that such %0aan obstacle as this should have impeded his progress, and have %0arendered powerless the hearty endeavours of some four hun- %0adred men. One thing, too, it is well known, more particularly %0asurprised 3 him, how it was possible that the fish, while ad- %0ahering to the ship, should arrest its progress, and yet should %0ahave no such power when brought on board. %0a%0aAccording to the persons who examined it on that occasion, %0aand who have seen it since, the echene'is bears a strong resem- %0ablance to a large slug. 9 The various opinions entertained %0arespecting it we have already 10 noticed, when speaking of it %0ain the Natural History of Fishes. There is no doubt, too, that %0aall fish of this kind are possessed of a similar power ; witn