rs. It is to be found also %0ain the Persian Gulf, where it is known by the name of "iace." %0aBut the most highly-esteemed of all, is that produced in the %0avicinity of the islands called Stcechades, 72 in the Gallic Gulf, %0aand near the JEolian Islands and the town of Drepana in the %0aSea of Sicily. Coral is to be found growing, too, at Graviscae, %0aand off the coast of Neapolis in Campania : as also at Erythrae, %0awhere it is intensely red, but soft, and consequently little %0avalued. %0a%0aIts form is that of a shrub, 73 and its colour green : its %0aberries are white and soft while under water, but the moment %0athey are removed from it, they become hard and red, resem- %0abling the berries of cultivated cornel in size and appearance. %0aThey say that, while alive, if it is only touched by a person, %0ait will immediately become as hard as stone ; and hence it is %0athat the greatest pains are taken to prevent this, by tearing it %0aup from the bottom with nets, or else cutting it short with %0aa sharp- edged instrument of iron : from which last circum- %0astance it is generally supposed to have received its name of %0a" curalium." 74 The reddest coral and the most branchy is %0aheld in the highest esteem ; but, at the same time, it must %0anot be rough or hard like stone ; nor yet, on the other hand, %0ashould it be full of holes or hollow. %0a%0aThe berries of coral are no less esteemed by the men in India %0athan are the pearls of that country by the females among us : %0atheir soothsayers, too, and diviners look upon coral as an amu- %0alet endowed with sacred properties, 75 and a sure preservative %0aagainst all dangers : hence it is that they equally value it as %0aan ornament and as an object of devotion. Before it was %0aknown in what estimation coral was held by the people of %0aIndia, the Gauls were in the habit of adorning their swords, %0a%0a72 See B. iii. c. 11. %0a%0a7S Theophrastus reckons coral among the precious stones, and the %0aPseudo-Orpheus among the minerals. Pliny would seem to be at a loss %0awhether to consider it as an animal or a vegetable. In reality it is the %0aproduction of marine organized bodies of an arborescent habit, known as %0aCorallina, with jointed stems, supported on a kind of root divided into %0abranches, which are likewise jointed. %0a%0a14 Because Ktiptirai, it is " cut short" in the 6ea, a far-fetched deriva- %0ation, apparently. %0a%0a75 Solinus informs us that Zoroaster attributed certain mysterious pro- %0aperties to coral. %0a%0a%0a%0a12 %0a%0a%0a%0apliny's natural history. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XXXII. %0a%0a%0a%0ashields, and helmets with it ; but at the present day, owing to %0athe value set upon it as an article of exportation, it has become %0aso extremely rare, that it is seldom to be seen even in the %0aregions that produce it. Branches of coral, hung at the neck %0aof infants, 76 are thought to act as a preservative against danger. %0aCalcined, pulverized, and taken in water, coral gives relief to %0apatients suffering from griping pains in the bowels, affections %0aof the bladder, and urinary calculi. Similarly taken in %0awine, or, if there are symptoms of fever, in water, it acts as a %0asoporific. It resists the action of fire a considerable time be- %0afore it is calcined. %0a%0aThere is also a statement made that if this medicament is %0afrequently taken internally, the spleen will be gradually con- %0asumed. Powdered coral, too, is an excellent remedy for pa- %0atients who bring up or spit blood. Calcined coral is used as %0aan ingredient in compositions for the eyes, being productive of %0acertain astringent and cooling effects : it makes flesh, also, in %0athe cavities left by ulcers, and effaces scars upon the skin. %0a%0aCHAP. 12. — THE ANTIPATHIES AND SYMPATHIES WHICH EXIST %0aBETWEEN CERTAIN OBJECTS. THE HATREDS MANIFESTED BY %0aCERTAIN AQUATIC ANIMALS. THE PASTINACA : EIGHT REME- %0aDIES. THE GALEOS : FIFTEEN REMEDIES. THE SUR- MULLET : %0aFIFTEEN RE