ook XXXII. %0a%0a%0a%0athe same colour as this last, covered with thin coats full of a %0aliquid of the consistency of honey mixed with wax, possessed %0aof a fetid smell, of a bitter, acrid taste, and friable to the %0atouch. %0a%0aThe most efficacious castoreum is that which comes from %0aPontus and Galatia, the next best being the produce of Africa. %0aWhen inhaled, it acts as a sternutatory. Mixed with oil of %0aroses and peucedanum, 85 and applied to the head, it is produc- %0ative of narcotic effects — a result which is equally produced by %0ataking it in water ; for which reason it is employed in the %0atreatment of phrenitis. Used as a fumigation, it acts as an %0aexcitant upon patients suffering from lethargy : and similarly %0aemployed, or used in the form of a suppository, it dispels hy- %0asterical* 6 suffocations. It acts also as an emmenagogue and as %0aan expellent of the afterbirth, being taken by the patient, in %0adoses of two drachmae, with pennyroyal, 87 in water. It is em- %0aployed also for the cure of vertigo, opisthotony, fits of trem- %0abling, spasms, affections of the sinews, sciatica, stomachic %0acomplaints, and paralysis, the patient either being rubbed with %0ait all over, or else taking it as an electuary, bruised and incor- %0aporated with seed of vitex, 88 vinegar, and oil of roses, to the %0aconsistency of honey. In the last form, too, it is taken for the %0acure of epilepsy, and in a potion, for the purpose of dispelling %0aflatulency and gripings in the bowels, and for counteracting the %0aeffects of poison. %0a%0aWhen taken as a potion, the only difference is in the mode %0aof mixing it, according to the poison that it is intended to %0aneutralize ; thus, for example, when it is taken for the sting %0aof the scorpion, wine is used as the medium ; and when for %0ainjuries inflicted by spiders or by the phalangium, 89 honied %0awine where it is intended to be brought up again, and rue %0awhere it is desirable that it should remain