 its conformation. Of tortoises, %0athere are various kinds, land tortoises, 99 sea tortoises, 1 tortoises 2 %0awhich live in muddy waters, and tortoises 2 which live in fresh ; %0athese last being known to some Greek authors by the name of %0a" emydes." The flesh of the land- tortoise is employed for %0afumigations more particularly, and we find it asserted that it %0ais highly salutary for repelling the malpractices of magic, and for %0a%0a91 Or Mistletoe ; see B. xvi. c. 92. %0a%0a95 As to tbe identity of the "nitrum" of the ancients, see B. xxxi. %0ac. 46 and the Notes. %0a%0a96 See B. xx. c. 76. %0a%0a97 Under the head of " testudines," he includes the tortoises, terra- %0apenes, and turtles, which form an order of reptiles, known in Natural %0aHistory as Chelonia, and characterised by the body being enclosed be- %0atween a double shield or shell, out of which protrude the head, tail, and %0afour extremities. %0a%0a98 See B. ix. cc. 11, 12. 99 Our tortoises so called. %0a%0a1 Our Chelonides, or turtles. %0a%0a2 The Emydes and Trionyches of Modern Natural History. %0a%0a%0a%0a16 %0a%0a%0a%0aflint's NATURAL HISTOEY. [Book XXXII. %0a%0a%0a%0aneutralizing poisons. These tortoises are found in the greatest %0anumbers in Africa ; where the head and feet being first cut off, %0ait is said, they are given to persons by way of antidote. %0aEaten, too, in a broth made from them, they are thought to %0adisperse scrofula, diminish the volume of the spleen, and effect %0athe cure of epilepsy. The blood of the land-tortoise improves %0athe eyesight, and removes cataract : it is kept also, made up %0awith meal into pills, which are given with wine when neces- %0asary, to neutralize the poison of all kinds of serpents, frogs, %0aspiders, and similar venomous Animals. It is found a useful %0aplan, too, in cases of glaucoma, to anoint the eyes with gall of %0atortoises, mixed with Attic honey, and, for the cure of injuries %0ainflicted by scorpions, to drop the gall into the wound. %0a%0aAshes of tortoiseshell, kneaded up with wine and oil, are %0aused for the cure of chaps upon the feet, and of ulcerations. %0aThe shavings of the surface of the shell, administered in drink, %0aact as an antaphrodisiac : a thing that is the more surprising, %0afrom the fact that a powder prepared from the whole of the shell %0ahas the reputation of being a strong aphrodisiac. As to the urine %0aof the land-tortoise, I do not think that it can be obtained %0aotherwise than by opening it and taking out the bladder ; this %0abeing one of those substances to which the adepts in magic %0aattribute such marvellous properties. For the sting of the %0aasp, they say, it is wonderfully effectual ; and even more 60, %0aif bugs are mixed with it. The eggs of the tortoise, hardened %0aby keeping, are applied to scrofulous sores and ulcers arising %0afrom burns or cold : they are taken also for pains in the %0astomach. %0a%0aThe flesh of the sea-tortoise, 3 mixed with that of frogs, is %0aan excellent remedy for injuries caused by the salamander; 4 %0aindeed there is nothing that is a better neutralizer of the secre- %0ations of the salamander than the sea-tortoise. The blood of %0athis animal reproduces the hair when lost through alopecy, %0aand is curative of porrigo and all kinds of ulcerations of the %0ahead ; the proper method of using it being to let it dry, and %0athen gently wash it off. For the cure of ear-ache, this blood %0ais injected with woman's milk, and for epilepsy it is eaten %0awith fine wheaten flour, three heminae of the blood being %0amixed with one hemina of vinegar. It is prescribed also for %0athe cure of asthma ; but in this cas%3ce in combination with one %0a3 Or turtle. * See B. x. c. 86. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 14.] %0a%0a%0a%0aTHE TORTOISE. %0a%0a%0a%0a17 %0a%0a%0a%0ahemina of wine. Sometimes, too, it is taken by asthmatic %0apatients, with barley-meal and vinegar, in pieces about the %0asize of a bean ; one of these pieces being taken each morn- %0aing and evening at first, but after some days, two in the %0aevening. In cases of epilepsy, the mouth of the patient %0ais opened and this blood introduced. For spasmodic affections, %0awhen not of a violent nature, it is injected, in combination with %0acastoreum, as a clyster. If a person rinses his teeth three %0atimes a year with blood of tortoises, he will be always ex- %0aempt from tooth-ache. This blood is also a cure for asthmatic %0aaffections, and for the malady called " orthopnoea," being admi- %0anistered for these purposes in polenta. %0a%0aThe gall of the tortoise improves the eye-sight, effaces scars, %0aand cures affections of the tonsillary glands, quinsy, and all %0akinds of diseases of the mouth, cancers of that part more par- %0aticularly, as well as cancer of the testes. Applied to the nos- %0atrils it dispels epilepsy, and sets the patient on his feet : %0aincorporated in vinegar with the slough of a snake, it is a %0asovereign remedy for purulent discharges from the ears. Some %0apersons add ox-gall and the broth of boiled tortoise-flesh, with %0aan equal proportion of snake's slough ; but in such case, care %0amust be taken to boil the tortoise in wine. Applied with %0ahoney, this gall is curative of all diseases of the eyes ; and %0afor the cure of cataract, gall of the sea-tortoise is used, in %0acombination with blood of the river- tortoise and milk. The %0ahair, too, of females, is dyed 5 with this gall. For the cure of %0ainjuries inflicted by the salamander, it will be quite sufficient %0ato drink the broth of boiled tortoise-flesh. %0a%0aThere is, again, a third 6 kind of tortoise, which inhabits mud %0aand swampy localities : the shell on its back is flat and broad, %0alike that upon the breast, and the callipash is not arched and %0arounded, the creature being altogether of a repulsive appear- %0aance. However, there are some remedial medicaments to be %0aderived even from this animal. Thus, for instance, three of %0athem are thr