is %0aremedy, Sallustius Dionysius 24 used to suspend frogs over %0aboiling vinegar by the hind legs, so as to make them discharge %0atheir humours into the vinegar by the mouth, using consider- %0aable numbers of frogs for the purpose : to those, however, who %0ahad a stronger stomach, he prescribed the frogs themselves, %0aeaten with their broth. It is generally thought, too, that %0athis recipe applies more particularly to the double teeth, and %0athat the vinegar prepared as above-mentioned, is remarkably %0auseful for strengthening them when loose. %0a%0aFor this last purpose, some persons cut off the legs of two %0afrogs, and then macerate the bodies in two hemina) of wine, %0arecommending this preparation as a collutory for strengthening %0aloose teeth. Others attach the frogs, whole, to the exterior of %0athe jaws i 25 and with some it is the practice to boil ten frogs, %0a%0a20 See Note 89 to Chapter 23 of this Book. %0a%0a21 "Canicula." See B. ix. cc. 11, 70. 22 Or stin»-ray. %0a23 Tunny cut in slices. See B, ix. c. 18. 2 * See end of B. xxxi. %0a25 For the purpose, probably, of assuaging the pain of tooth-ache by %0a%0atheir coolness, %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 27.] %0a%0a%0a%0aREMEDIES FOR LICHENS. %0a%0a%0a%0a35 %0a%0a%0a%0ain three sextarii of vinegar, down to one-third, and to use the %0adecoction as a strengthener of loose teeth. By certain autho- %0arities, too, it has been recommended to boil the hearts of six- %0aand-thirty frogs beneath a copper vessel, in one sextarius of old %0aoil, and then to inject the decoction into the ear on the same %0aside of the jaw as the part affected : while others again have %0aused, as an application for the teeth, a frog's liver, boiled, and %0abeaten up with honey. All the preparations above described %0awill be found still more efficacious if made from the sea- %0afrog. 25 In cases where the teeth are carious and emit an %0aoffensive smell, it is recommended to dry some whale's 27 flesh %0ain an oven for a night, and then to add an equal quantity of %0asalt, and use the mixture as a dentifrice. " Enhydris" 28 is the %0aname given by the Greeks to a snake that lives in the water. %0aWith the four upper teeth of this reptile, it is the practice, for %0athe cure of aching in the upper teeth, to lance the upper gums, %0aand with the four lower teeth, for aching in the lower. Some %0apersons, however, content themselves with using an eyetooth %0aonly. Ashes, too, of burnt crabs are used for this purpose; %0aand the murex, reduced to ashes, makes an excellent den- %0atifrice. %0a%0aCHAP. 27. — REMEDIES FOE. LICHENS, AND FOE SPOTS UPON THE %0aFACE. THE DOIPHIN : NINE REMEDIES. COLUTHIA OR CORT- %0aPHIA : THREE REMEDIES. HALCYONEDM : SEVEN REMEDIES. %0aTHE TUNNY : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%0aLichens and leprous spots are removed by applying the fat %0aof the sea-calf, 29 ashes of the msena 30 in combination with three %0aoboli of honey, liver of the pastinaca 31 boiled in oil, or ashes %0aof the dolphin or hippocampus 32 mixed with water. After the %0aparts have been duly excoriated, a cicatrizing treatment ought %0ato be pursued. Some persons bake dolphin's liver in an %0aearthen vessel, till a grease flows therefrom like oil 33 in ap- %0a%0a2fl See B. ix. cc. 40, 67. 27 " Cetum." See B. ix. cc. 40, 74. %0a%0a28 Ajasson is of opinion that here and in c. 19 Pliny has mistaken the %0aotter for a serpent, the mammiferae only having eye or canine teeth. %0aAristotle, Hist. Anim. B. i. c. i., calls the otter by the name of "Enhy- %0adris." See B. xxx. c. 8, where Pliny speaks of the "Enhydris" as a %0a" male white serpent." 29 Or seal. See B. ix. c. 15. %0a%0a30 See B. ix. c. 42. Holland calls the raaena the " cackerel." %0a%0a31 Or sting-ray. « g ee j X- C- i, %0a%0a33 Much like the cod-liver oil, held in such high repute at the present day. %0a%0aD 2 %0a%0a%0a%0ai*6 %0a%0a%0a%0aPLINY'S NATURAL HISTOKT. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XXXII. %0a%0a%0a%0apearance : this they use by way of ointment for these dis- %0aeases. %0a%0aBurnt shells of the murex or purple, applied with honey, %0ahave a detergent effect upon spots on the face in females: %0aused as an application for seven consecutive days, a fomenta- %0ation made of white of eggs being substituted on the eighth, %0athey efface wrinkles, and plump out the skin. To the genus %0a" murex" belong the shell-fish known by the Greeks as " co- %0aluthia" or " coryphia," equally turbinated, but considerably %0asmaller : for all the above purposes they are still more effica- %0acious, and the use of them tends to preserve the sweetness of %0athe breath. Fish-glue 34 effaces wrinkles and plumps out the skin; %0abeing boiled for the purpose in water some four hours, and then %0apounded and kneaded up till it attains a thin consistency, like %0athat of honey. After being thus prepared, it is put by in a new %0avessel for keeping ; and, when wanted for use, is mixed, in %0athe proportion of four drachmae, with two drachma? of sulphur, %0atwo of alkanet, and eight of litharge ; the whole beiDg %0asprinkled with water and beaten up together. The prepara- %0ation is then applied to the face, and is washed off at the end %0aof four hours. For the cure of freckles and other affections %0aof the face, calcined bones of cuttle-fish are also used ; an %0aapplication which is equally good for the removal of fleshy %0aexcrescences and the dispersion of running sores. %0a%0a(8.) For the cure of itch-scab, a frog is boiled in five semisex- %0atarii of sea-water, the decoction being reduced to the consistency %0aof honey. There is a sea production called " halcyon eum," com- %0aposed, as some think, of the nests 35 of the birds known as the %0a"halcyon" 36 and "ceyx," or, according to others, of the con- %0acretion of sea-foam, or of some slime of the sea, or a certain %0alanuginous inflorescence thrown up by it. Of this halcyoneum %0athere are four different kinds ; the first, of an ashy colour, of a %0acompact substance, and possessed of a pungent odour ; the %0asecond, soft, of a milder nature, and with a smell almost iden- %0a%0a34 " Icthyocolla." See Chapter 24 of the present Book. %0a%0a33 Of course this assertion as to the nest of the kingfisher is altogether %0afahulous, and the sea-productions here described by Pliny were lon» con- %0asidered, though destitute of leaves, flowers, and fruit, to belong to the %0avegetable kingdom. Peyssonnel, however, made the discovery that they %0abelong to the animal kingdom, and that they owe their origin to a species %0aof polyp. %0a%0a3 » Or kingfisher. See B. x. c. 47. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 28.] %0a%0a%0a%0aREMEDIES FOR SCROFULA, %0a%0a%0a%0a37 %0a%0a%0a%0atical with that of sea-weed ; the third, whiter, and with a %0avariegated surface ; the fourth, more like pumice in appear- %0aance, and closely resembling rotten sponge. The best of all is %0athat which nearty borders upon a purple hue, and is known as %0athe " Milesian" kind : the whiter it is, the less highly it is %0aesteemed. %0a%0aThe properties of halcyoneum are ulcerative and detergent : %0awhen required for use, it is parched and applied without oil . %0aIt is quite marvellous how efficiently it removes leprous sores, %0alichens, and freckles, used in combination with lupines and %0atwo oboli of sulphur. It is employed, also, for the removal %0aof marks upon the eyes. 37 Andreas 38 has recommended for the %0acure of leprosy ashes of burnt crabs, with oil ; and Attalus, 39 %0afresh fat of tunny. %0a%0aCHAP. 28. — REMEDIES FOR SCROFULA, IMPOSTHTTMES OF THE PA- %0aROTID GLANDS, aUINSY, AND DISEASES OF THE FAUCES. THE %0aJUBNA : THIRTEEN REMEDIES. THE SEA-SCOLOPENDRA ! TWO %0aREMEDIES. THE SAUHUS : ONE REMEDY. SHELL-FISH : ONE %0aREMEDY. THE SILURUS : FIFTEEN REMEDIES. %0a%0aUlcerations of the mouth are cured by an application ^ of %0abrine in which maense 40 have been pickled, in combination with %0acalcined heads of the fish, and honey. Tor the cure of scro- %0afula, it is a good plan to prick the sores with the small bone %0athat is found in the tail of the fish known as the sea-frog ; 41 %0acare being taken to avoid making a wound, and to repeat the %0aoperation daily, until a perfect cure is effected. The same %0aproperty, too, belongs to the sting of the pastinaca, and to the %0asea-hare, applied topically to the sores : but in both cases due %0acare must be taken to remove them in an instant. Shells of %0asea-urchins are bruised, also, and applied with vinegar ; shells %0aalso of sea-scolopendrae, 42 applied with honey ; and river-crabs %0apounded or calcined, and applied with honey. Bones, too, of %0athe ssepia, triturated and applied with stale axle-grease, are %0amarvellously useful for this purpose. %0a%0aS7 " Oculorum cicatrices." 38 See end of B. xx. %0a%0a39 See end of B. via. 40 See B. ix. c. 42. %0a%0a41 See B. ix. cc. 40, 67. The Bamberg MS. has here " rhine " (the %0atish again mentioned in Chapter 53 of this Book) instead of "rana; ' a %0areading which Sillig rejects. Hardouin conjectures that "raia" is the %0acorrect reading, the sea-frog having no sting or stickle in the tail. %0a%0a** See B. ix. c. 67. %0a%0a%0a%0a38 flint's NATURAL HISTOBT. [Book XXXII. %0a%0a%0a%0aThis last preparation is used, also, for the cure of lmpost- %0ahumes of the parotid glands ; a purpose for which the liver %0aof the sea-fish known as the " saurus" 43 is employed. Nay, %0aeven more than this, fragments of earthen vessels in which %0asalt fish have been kept are pounded with stale axle-grease, %0aand applied to scrofulous sores and imposthumes of the parotid %0aglands ; as also calcined murex, incorporated with oil. Stiffness %0ain the neck is allayed by taking what are known as sea-lice, 43 ' %0ain doses of one drachma in drink, taking castoreum 44 mixed %0awith pepper in honied wine, or making a decoction of frogs in %0aoil and salt, and taking the liquor. %0a%0aOpisthotony, too, and tetanus are treated in a similar manner; %0aand spasms, with the addition of pepper. Ashes of burnt %0aheads of salted maenoe are applied externally, with honey, for the %0acure of quinsy ; as also a decoction of frogs, boiled in vinegar, %0aa preparation which is equally good for affections of the tonsil- %0alary glands. River-crabs, pounded, one to each hemina of %0awater, are used as a gargle for the cure of quinsy ; or else %0athey are taken with wine and hot water. Garum, 45 put beneath %0athe uvula with a spoon, effectually cures diseases of that part. %0aThe silurus, 46 used as food, either fresh or salted, improves the %0avoice. %0a%0aCHAP. 29. REMEDIES FOR COUGH AND DISEASES OF THE CHEST. %0a%0aSurmullets act as an emetic, dried and pounded, and taken %0ain drink. Castoreum, taken fasting, with a small quantity of %0ahammoniacum 47 in oxymel, is extremely good for asthma : %0aspasms, too, in the stomach are assuaged by taking a similar %0apotion with warm oxymel. Frogs stewed in their own liquor %0ain the saucepan, the same way in fact that fish are dressed, %0aare good for a cough, it is said. In some cases, also, frogs are %0asuspended by the legs, and after their juices 48 have been received %0ain a platter, it is recommended to gut them, and the entrails %0abeing first carefully removed, to preserve them for the above %0a%0a43 Or sea-lizard, a fish again mentioned in Chapter 53 of this Book. %0aJElian also speaks of it, Hist. Nat. B. xii. c. 25 ; but it has not been %0ahitherto identified. See c. 25 of this Book %0a%0a«* See c. 13 of this Book. « See B. xxxi c 43 %0a%0a« See B. ix. cc. 17, 25, 75. %0a%0a47 It is not clear whether he means the gum ammoniac of B. xii. c. 49 %0aand B. xxiv. c. 14, or the sal ammoniac of 15. xxxi. c. 39. %0a%0a48 "Saliva." See the recipe of Sallustius Dionysius in Chapter 26 of %0athis Book. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 31. J REMEDIES FOB, DISEASES OF THE BOWELS. 39 %0a%0apurpose. There is a small frog, 49 also, which ascends trees, and %0acroaks aloud there : if a persou suffering from cough spits into %0aits mouth and then lets it go, he will experience a cure, it is said. %0aFor cough attended with spitting of blood, it is recommended %0ato beat up the raw flesh of a snail, and to drink it in hot water. %0a%0aCHAP. 30. (9.) REMEDIES FOR FAINS IN THE LIVER AND SIDE. %0a%0aTHE ELONGATED CONCH : SIX REMEDIES. THE TETHEA : FIVE %0aREMEDIES. %0a%0aFor pains in the liver, a sea-scorpion is killed in wine, and %0athe liquid is taken. The meat, too, of the elongated conch 50 is %0ataken with honied wine and water, in equal quantities, or, if %0athere are symptoms of fever, with hyd'romel. Pains in the %0aside are assuaged by taking the flesh of the hippocampus, 61 %0agrilled, or else the tethea, 61 * very similar to the oyster, with %0athe ordinary food. For sciatica, the pickle of the silurus is %0ainjected, by way of clyster. The flesh of conchs, too, is pre- %0ascribed, for fifteen days, in doses of three oboli soaked in two %0asextarii of wine. %0a%0aCHAP. 31. — REMEDIES FOR DISEASES OF THE BOWELS. SEA-WORT : %0aONE REMEDY. THE MYAX : TWENTY-FIVE REMEDIES. THE MITU- %0aLUS ! EIGHT REMEDIES. TELOEIDES : ONE REMEDY. SEK1PHUM: %0aTWO REMEDIES. THE ERYTHINITS : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe silurus, 52 taken in its broth, or the torpedo, 53 used as %0afood, acts as a laxative upon the bowels. There is a sea-wort, 51 %0aalso, similar in appearance to the cultivated cabbage : it is %0ainjurious to the' stomach, but acts most efficiently as a purga- %0ative, requiring to be cooked with fat meat for the purpose, in %0aconsequence of its extreme acridity. The broth, too, of all %0aboiled fish is good for this purpose ; it acting, also, as a strong %0adiuretic, taken with wine more particularly. The best kind %0aof all is that prepared from the sea-scorpion, the iulis, 55 and %0a%0a49 The Dryophites of Rondelet, Dalechamps says. %0a%0a60 Identical with the Strombus of cc. 39, 46, and 53 of this Book. %0a%0a" See B. ix. c. 1. %0a%0a«• Littre remarks that Pliny here seems to speak of the "Tethea" as %0aa mollusk ; whereas in c. 31, from his expression " Fungorum venus %0ageneris quam piscium," he would appear to be describing a zoophyte. %0a%0a" See B. ix. cc. 17, 25, 75. %0a%0a« See B. ix. cc. 24, 48, 67, 74, 75. 54 See B. xx. c. 38. %0a%0a85 A rock fish, according to Atheneeus, B. vii. Eondelet, B. vi. c. 7, %0aidentifies it with' the fish, called girdlo by the people of Liguria, the don- %0asella of other districts. %0a%0a%0a%0a40 %0a%0a%0a%0apliity's natural history. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XXXII. %0a%0a%0a%0arock-fish in general, as they are destitute of all rankness and %0aare free from fat. The proper way of cooking them is with %0adill, parsley, coriander, and leeks, with the addition of oil and %0asalt. Stale cybium, 66 too, acts as a purgative, and is particularly %0auseful for carrying on 0 crudities, pituitous humours, and bile. %0a%0aThe myax 57 is of a purgative nature, a shell-fish of which %0awe shall take this opportunity of giving the natural his- %0atory at length. These fish collect together in masses, like the %0aiuurex, 58 and are found in spots covered with sea-weed. They %0aare the finest eating in autumn, and are found in the greatest %0aperfection in places where fresh-water streams discharge them- %0aselves into the sea ; for which reason it is that those of Egypt %0aare held in such high esteem. As the winter advances, they %0acontract a bitter flavour, and assume a reddish hue. The %0aliquor of these fish, it is said, acts as a purgative upon the %0abowels and bladder, has a detergent effect upon the intestines, %0aacts aperiently upon all the passages, purges the kidneys, and %0adiminishes the blood and adipose secretions. Hence it is that %0athese shell-fish are found of the greatest use for the treatment %0aof dropsy, for the regulation of the catamenia, and for the re- %0amoval of jaundice, all diseases of the joints, and flatulency. %0aThey are very good, also, for the reduction of obesity, for %0adiseases of the bile and of the pituitous secretions, for affec- %0ations of the lungs, liver, and spleen, and for rheumatic de- %0afluxions. The only inconvenience resulting from them is, that %0athey irritate the throat and impede the articulation. They %0ahave, also, a healing effect upon ulcers of a serpiginous nature, %0aor which stand in need of detergents, as also upon carcinoma- %0atous sores. Calcined, the same way as the murex, and em- %0aployed with honey, they are curative of bites inflicted either %0aby dogs or human beings, and of leprous spots or freckles. The %0aashes of them, rinsed, are good for the removal of films upon %0athe eyes, granulations of those organs and indurations of the %0amembrane, as also for diseases of the gums and teeth, and for %0apituitous eruptions. They serve, also, as an antidote to doryc- %0anium 59 and to opocarpathon. 60 %0a%0a56 Sliced tunny. See E. ix. c. 18. %0a%0a57 A genus which comprises the "myes," mentioned in B. ix. c 56 %0aaccording to Dalechamps. %0a%0a515 See B. ix. c. 60. 59 g ee g xxi c 1Q5 %0a%0a60 See B. xxviii. c. 45, and Chapter 20 of the present Book. %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 31.] EEAIKDIES FOE DISEASES OF THE BOWELS. %0a%0a%0a%0a41 %0a%0a%0a%0aThere are two species of this shell-fish, of a degenerate kind : %0athe mitulus, 61 which has a strong flavour, and a saltish taste ; %0aand the myisca, 62 which differs from the former in the roundness %0aof its shell, is somewhat smaller, and is covered with filaments, %0athe shell being thinner, and the meat of a sweeter flavour. The %0aashes, also, of the mitulus, like those of the murex, are pos- %0asessed of certain caustic properties, and are very useful for the %0aremoval of leprous spots, freckles, and blemishes of the skin. %0aThey are rinsed, too, in the same manner as lead, 63 for the %0aremoval of swellings of the eyelids, of indurations of the %0amembranes, and of films upon the eyes, as also of sordid ulcers %0aupon other parts of the body, and of pustules upon the head. %0aThe meat of them, also, is employed as an application for bites %0ainflicted by dogs. %0a%0aAs to pelorides, 64 they act as a gentle laxative upon the %0abowels, an effect equally produced by castoreum, taken in doses %0aof two drachmae, in hydromel : where, however, a more drastic %0apurgative is recpiired, one drachma of dried garden-cucumber %0aroot is added, and two drachmae of aphronitrum. 69 The %0atethea 66 is good for griping pains in the bowels and for attacks %0aof flatulency : they are generally found adhering to the leaves %0aof marine plants, sucking their nutriment therefrom, and may %0abe rather looked upon as a sort of fungus than as a fish. They %0aare useful, also, for the removal of tenesmus and of diseases of %0athe kidneys. %0a%0aThere grows also in the sea a kind of absinthium, known by %0asome persons as " seriphum," 67 and found in the vicinity of %0aTaposiris, 68 in Egypt, more particularly. It is of a more %0aslender form than the land absinthium, acts as a purgative %0aupon the bowels, and effectually removes intestinal worms. %0aThe ssepia, too, is a laxative ; for which purpose these fish are %0a%0a61 Identical with our mussel, probably. %0a%0a62 Holland identifies this with the cockle, but it is probably a smaller %0akind of mussel. 63 See B. xxxiv. c. 50. %0a%0a61 We learn from Chapter 53 of this Book, that one class of the %0a"Cbamae," or gaping cockles, was known as "Pelorides." Horace also %0amentions them. %0a%0a65 See B. xxxi. c. 46. %0a%0a66 See Note 51 above. Sillig would here read " tetheum," apparently, %0ain the singular. ' 67 Described in B. xxvii. c. 29. %0a%0a6S A city not far from the Canopic branch of the Kile. %0a%0a%0a%0a42 %0a%0a%0a%0apunt's natural history. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XXXII %0a%0a%0a%0aadministered 69 with the food, hoiled with a mixture of oil, salt, %0aand meal. Salted mamae, 70 applied with bull's gall to the navel, %0aacts as a purgative upon the bowels. %0a%0aThe liquor of fish, boiled in the saucepan with lettuces, dispels %0atenesmus. River-crabs, 71 beaten up and taken with water, act %0aastringently upon the bowels, and they have a diuretic effect, if %0ataken with white wine. Deprived of the legs, and taken in %0adoses of three oboli with myrrh and iris, one drachma of each, %0athey disperse urinary calculi. For the cure of the iliac pas- %0asion and of attacks of flatulency, castoreum 72 should be taken, %0awith seed of daucus 73 and of parsley, a pinch in three fingers %0aof each, the whole being mixed with four cyathi of warm %0ahonied wine. Griping pains in the bowels should be treated %0awith castoreum and a mixture of dill and wine. The fish %0acalled " erythinus," 74 used as food, acts astringently upon the %0abowels. Dysentery is cured by taking frogs boiled with squills, %0aand prepared in the form of boluses, or else hearts of frogs %0abeaten up with honey, as Niceratus 76 recommends. For the %0acure of jaundice, salt fish should be taken with pepper, the %0apatient abstaining from all other kinds of meat. %0a%0aCHAP. 32. REMEDIES FOE DISEASES OF THE SPLEEN, FOE URI- %0aNARY CALCULI, AND FOE AFFECTIONS OF THE BLADDER. THE %0aSOLE : ONE EEMEDY. THE TURBOT : ONE EEMEDY. THE %0aBLENDIUS : ONE EEMEDY. THE SKA- NETTLE : SEVEN REMEDIES. %0aTHE PULMO MAEINUS : SIX EEMEDIES. ONYCHES : FOUR RE- %0aMEDIES. %0a%0aFor the cure of spleen diseases, the fish known as the sole 76 %0ais applied to that part ; the torpedo, 77 also, or else a live tur- %0abot; 78 it being then set at liberty in the sea. The sea- %0ascorpion, 79 killed in wine, is a cure for diseases of the bladder %0a%0a69 " Dantur " seems a preferable reading to " datur " %0a%0a70 See B. ix c. 42. %0a%0a71 Our crawfish, the Astacus potamobios of Leach. %0a%0a72 See Chapter 13 of this Book. %0a%0a73 See B. xix. c. 27, and B. xxv. c. 64. %0a%0a74 See B. ix. cc. 23, 77. 75 See end of B xxxi %0a%0a76 See B. ix. cc. 20, 24, 36. %0a%0a77 See B. ix. cc. 24, 48, 67, 74, 75. %0a%0a« " Rhombus." See B. ix. cc. 20, 36,