fevers, the patient being anointed with the preparation just %0abefore the paroxysms come on : some authorities recommend %0athe addition of pepper to the mixture. Others prescribe for %0aquartan fevers a decoction of river-crabs in wine, boiled down %0ato one fourth, the patient taking it at the moment of leaving %0athe bath : by some, too, it is recommended to swallow the left %0aeye of a river-crab. The magicians engage to cure a tertian %0afever, by attaching as an amulet to the patient, before sunrise, %0athe eyes of river-crabs, the crabs when thus blinded being set %0aat liberty in the water. They say, too, that these eyes, attached %0ato the body in a piece of deer's hide, with the flesh of a %0anightingale, 32 will dispel sleep and promote watchfulness. In %0acases where there are symptoms of lethargy, the rennet of the %0abalsena 33 or of the sea-calf 34 is given to the patient to smell ; %0asome persons, too, use the blood of tortoises as a liniment for %0alethargic patients. %0a%0aTertian fevers, it is said, may be cured by wearing one of %0athe vertebrae 35 of a perch attached to the body, and quartan %0afevers by using fresh river snails, as an aliment. Some per- %0asons preserve these snails in salt for this purpose, and give %0athem, pounded, in drink. %0a%0a» See B. ix. c. 24. » "Ablatis unguibus." %0a%0a30 "Rubeta." 3i 0ur crawfish. %0a%0a32 Because the nightingale sings at night, instead of sleeping %0a%0a33 See B. ix. cc. 2, 5, 6, 7, 15. 34 0r stal%3c 35 « Spondylus." %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 40.] %0a%0a%0a%0aREMEDIES FOE BURNS. %0a%0a%0a%0a49 %0a%0a%0a%0aCHAP. 39. EEMEDIES FOR LETHARGY, CACHEXY, AND DROPSY. %0a%0aStrombi, 36 left to putrefy in vinegar, act as an excitant upon %0alethargic patients by their smell ; they are very useful, too, %0afor tlie cure of cardiac diseases. For cachectic patients, where %0athe body is wasting with consumption, tethese 37 are considered %0abeneficial, mixed with rue and honey. For the cure of %0adropsy, dolphin's fat is melted and taken with wine, the re- %0apulsive taste of it being neutralized by first touching the %0anostrils with unguent or some other odoriferous substance, or %0aelse by plugging the nostrils in some way or other. The flesh %0aof strombi, pounded and given in three heminse of honied %0awine and the same quantity of water, or, if there is fever, %0ain hydromel, is very useful for dropsy: the same, too, with %0athe juice of river-crabs, administered with honey. Water %0afrogs, too, are boiled with old wine and spelt, 3 '* and taken as %0afood, the liquor in which they have been boiled being drunk %0afrom the same vessel : or else the feet, head, and tail of a %0atortoise are cut off, and the intestines removed, the rest of %0athe flesh being seasoned in such a manner as to allow of %0aits being taken without loathing. River-crabs, too, eaten with %0atheir broth, are said to be very good for the cure of phthisis. %0a%0aCHAP. 40. REMEDIES FOR BURNS AND FOR ERYSIPELAS. %0a%0aBurns are cured by applying ashes of calcined sea-crabs or %0ariver-crabs with oil : fish-glue, too, and calcined frogs are %0aused as an application for scalds produced by boiling water. %0aThe same treatment also restores the hair, provided the ashes %0aare those of river-crabs : it is generally thought, too, that the %0apreparation should be applied with wax and bears' grease. %0aAshes, too, of burnt beaver- skin are very useful for these %0apurposes. Live frogs act as a check upon erysipelas, the belly %0aside being applied to the part affected : it is recommended, %0atoo, to attach them lengthwise by the hinder legs, so as to %0arender them more beneficial by reason of their increased re- %0aspiration. 38 Heads, too, of salted siluri 39 are reduced to ashes %0aand applied with vinegar. %0a%0aPrurigo and itch-scab, not only in man but in quadrupeds %0a%0a36 See Chapter 29 of this Book. %0a%0a37 See Chapters 30 and 31 of the present Book. 37 * See B. xviii. c. 19. %0a%0a38 " Crebriore anhelitu." 39 See B. ix. cc. 17, 25, 75. %0aVOL. VI. E %0a%0a%0a%0a50 %0a%0a%0a%0aPLINY's NATURAL BISTORT. [Book XXXII- %0a%0a%0a%0aas well, are most efficaciously treated with the liver of the %0apastinaea 40 boiled in oil. %0a%0aCHAP. 41. REMEDIES TOR DISEASES OF THE SINEWS. %0a%0aThe exterior callosity with which the flesh of purples is %0acovered, beaten up, unites the sinews, even when they have %0abeen severed asunder. It is a good plan, for patients suffering %0afrom tetanus, to take sea-calf s rennet in wine, in doses of one %0aobolus, as also fish-glue. 41 Persons affected with fits of trem- %0abling find much relief from castoreum, 42 provided they arc %0awell anointed with oil. I find it stated that the surmullet, 4 ' %0aused as an article of diet, acts injuriously upon the sinews. %0a%0aCHAP. 42. — METHODS OF ARRESTING HAEMORRHAGE AND OF LET- %0aTING ELOOD. THE POLYP : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aFish, used as. an aliment, it is generally thought, make %0ablood. The polyp, 44 bruised and applied, arrests haemorrhage, %0ait is thought: in addition to which we find stated the follow- %0aing particulars respecting it — that of itself it emits a sort of %0abrine, in consequence of which, there is no necessity to use %0aany in cooking it — that it should always be sliced with a reed %0a— "and that it is spoilt by using an iron knife, becoming tainted %0athereby, owing to the antipathy 45 which naturally exists %0a[between it and iron]. For the purpose also of arresting %0aheemorrhage, ashes of burnt frogs are applied topically, or else %0athe dried blood of those animals. Some authorities recom- %0amend the frog to be used, that is known by the Greeks as %0a" calamites," 46 from the fact that it lives among reeds 47 and %0ashrubs ; it is the smallest and greenest of all the frogs, and %0aeither the blood or the ashes of it are recommended to be em- %0aployed. Others, again, prescribe, in cases of bleeding at the %0anostrils, an injection of the ashes of young water-frogs, in the %0atadpole state, calcined in a new earthen vessel. %0a%0aio Or sting-ray. See B. ix. cc. 37, 40, 67, 72. %0a%0a41 Ichthyocolla. See Chapter 24 of this Book. %0a%0a42 See Chapter 13 of this Book. « See B. ix. c. 30. %0a« See B. ix. c. 46. %0a%0a*• This seems to be the meaning of " natura dissidente," if it is the %0acorrect reading. That, however, suggested by Dalechamps would seem %0ato be preferable, " natura retinente,"— " it being the nature of its flesh to %0acling to the knife." %0a%0a« See Chapter 24 of this Book. « " Calami." %0a%0a%0a%0aChap. 43.] EXTRACTION OF FOREIGN BODIES FROM FLESH. 51 %0a%0aOn the other hand, again, in cases where it is required to %0alet blood, the kind of leech is used which is known among %0aus by the name of " sanguisuga. 48 " Indeed, the action of %0athese leeches is looked upon as pretty much the same as that %0aof the cupping-glasses 49 used in medicine, their effect being to %0arelieve the body of superfluous blood, and to open the pores of %0athe skin. Still, however, there is this inconvenience attend- %0aing them — when they have been once applied, they create a %0anecessity 60 for having recourse to the same treatment at about %0athe same period in every succeeding year. Many physicians %0ahave been of opinion also, that leeches may be successfully ap- %0aplied in cases of gout. When gorged, they fall off in conse- %0aquence of losing their hold through the weight of the blood, %0abut if not, they must be sprinkled with salt 81 for the purpose. %0a%0aLeeches are apt, however, to leave their heads buried in the %0aflesh ; the consequence of which is an incurable wound, which %0ahas caused death in many cases, that of Messalinus, 52 for ex- %0aample, a patrician of consular rank, after an application of %0aleeches to his knee. When this is the case, that which was %0aintended as a remedy is turned into an active poison ; 53 a result %0awhich is to be apprehended in using the red leeches more %0aparticularly. Hence it is that when these last are employed, %0ait is the practice to snip them with a pair of scissors while %0asucking ; the consequence of which is, that the blood oozes %0aforth, through a siphon, as it were, and the head, gradually %0acontracting as the animal dies, is not left behind in the wound. %0aThere is a natural antipathy 54 existing between leeches and %0abugs, and hence it is that the latter are killed by the aid %0aof a fumigation made with leeches. Ashes of beaver-skin %0aburnt with tar, kneaded up with leek-juice, arrest bleeding at %0athe nostrils. %0a%0aCHAP. 43. — METHODS OF EXTRACTING FOREIGN BODIES FROM %0aTHE FLESH. %0a%0aTo extract pointed weapons which have pierced the flesh, %0aashes of calcined shells of the ssepia are used, as also of the %0a%0a48 "Bloodsuckers." *» " Cucurbitae medicinales." %0a%0a511 This does not appear to he considered the case at the present day. %0aSl A method still employed. 52 See B. X. c. 27. %0a%0a53 " lnvehunt virus remedio -verso." The reading is probably corrupt, %0abut the meaning is pretty evident. %0a%0a54 See B. xxix. c. 17, and c. 47 of this Book. %0a%0aE 2 %0a%0a%0a%0a.52 %0a%0a%0a%0aflint's natueal history. %0a%0a%0a%0a[Book XXXII. %0a%0a%0a%0apurple, the meat of salted fish, bruised river- crabs, or flesh %0aof the silurus 55 (a river-fish that is found in other streams %0aas well as the Nilus 56 ), applied either fresh or salted. The %0aashes also of this fish, as well as the fat, have the property of %0aextracting pointed bodies, and the back-bone, in a calcined %0astate, is used as a substitute for spodium. 67 %0a%0aCHAP. 44. — EEMEDIES FOE ULCEUS, CAECTNOMATA, AND CAE- %0aBTTNCLES. %0a%0aUlcers of a serpiginous nature, as also the fleshy excrescences %0awhich make their appearance in them, are kept in check by %0aapplying ashes of calcined heads of maense, 58 or else ashes of %0athe silurus. 69 Carcinomata, too, are treated with heads of %0asalted perch, their efficacy being considerably increased by 