shrub, 73 and its colour green : its %0a%3c berries are white and soft while under water, but the moment %0a%3c they are removed from it, they become hard and red, resem- %0a%3c bling the berries of cultivated cornel in size and appearance. %0a%3c They say that, while alive, if it is only touched by a person, %0a%3c it will immediately become as hard as stone ; and hence it is %0a%3c that the greatest pains are taken to prevent this, by tearing it %0a%3c up from the bottom with nets, or else cutting it short with %0a%3c a sharp- edged instrument of iron : from which last circum- %0a%3c stance it is generally supposed to have received its name of %0a%3c " curalium." 74 The reddest coral and the most branchy is %0a%3c held in the highest esteem ; but, at the same time, it must %0a%3c not be rough or hard like stone ; nor yet, on the other hand, %0a%3c should it be full of holes or hollow. %0a%3c %0a%3c The berries of coral are no less esteemed by the men in India %0a%3c than are the pearls of that country by the females among us : %0a%3c their soothsayers, too, and diviners look upon coral as an amu- %0a%3c let endowed with sacred properties, 75 and a sure preservative %0a%3c against all dangers : hence it is that they equally value it as %0a%3c an ornament and as an object of devotion. Before it was %0a%3c known in what estimation coral was held by the people of %0a%3c India, the Gauls were in the habit of adorning their swords, %0a%3c %0a%3c 72 See B. iii. c. 11. %0a%3c %0a%3c 7S Theophrastus reckons coral among the precious stones, and the %0a%3c Pseudo-Orpheus among the minerals. Pliny would seem to be at a loss %0a%3c whether to consider it as an animal or a vegetable. In reality it is the %0a%3c production of marine organized bodies of an arborescent habit, known as %0a%3c Corallina, with jointed stems, supported on a kind of root divided into %0a%3c branches, which are likewise jointed. %0a%3c %0a%3c 14 Because Ktiptirai, it is " cut short" in the 6ea, a far-fetched deriva- %0a%3c tion, apparently. %0a%3c %0a%3c 75 Solinus informs us that Zoroaster attributed certain mysterious pro- %0a%3c perties to coral. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 12 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny's natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXXII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c shields, and helmets with it ; but at the present day, owing to %0a%3c the value set upon it as an article of exportation, it has become %0a%3c so extremely rare, that it is seldom to be seen even in the %0a%3c regions that produce it. Branches of coral, hung at the neck %0a%3c of infants, 76 are thought to act as a preservative against danger. %0a%3c Calcined, pulverized, and taken in water, coral gives relief to %0a%3c patients suffering from griping pains in the bowels, affections %0a%3c of the bladder, and urinary calculi. Similarly taken in %0a%3c wine, or, if there are symptoms of fever, in water, it acts as a %0a%3c soporific. It resists the action of fire a considerable time be- %0a%3c fore it is calcined. %0a%3c %0a%3c There is also a statement made that if this medicament is %0a%3c frequently taken internally, the spleen will be gradually con- %0a%3c sumed. Powdered coral, too, is an excellent remedy for pa- %0a%3c tients who bring up or spit blood. Calcined coral is used as %0a%3c an ingredient in compositions for the eyes, being productive of %0a%3c certain astringent and cooling effects : it makes flesh, also, in %0a%3c the cavities left by ulcers, and effaces scars upon the skin. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 12. — THE ANTIPATHIES AND SYMPATHIES WHICH EXIST %0a%3c BETWEEN CERTAIN OBJECTS. THE HATREDS MANIFESTED BY %0a%3c CERTAIN AQUATIC ANIMALS. THE PASTINACA : EIGHT REME- %0a%3c DIES. THE GALEOS : FIFTEEN REMEDIES. THE SUR- MULLET : %0a%3c FIFTEEN REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c In reference to that repugnance which exists between cer- %0a%3c tain things, known to the Greeks as " antipathia," there is %0a%3c nothing more venomous 77 than the pastinaca, a sea-fish which %0a%3c kills trees even with its sting, as already 78 stated. And yet, %0a%3c poisonous as it is, the galeos 79 pursues it; a fish which, %0a%3c %0a%3c 76 A practice still retained, though the original intention of it has heen %0a%3c lost sight of. As to the form of the coral now used by infants, see %0a%3c Note 85 to B. xxviii. c. 7. %0a%3c %0a%3c 17 In reality, the Pastinaca or Sting-ray is not venomous ; but the %0a%3c wounds inflicted by the sting in its tail are highly dangerous, from their %0a%3c tendency to gangrene %0a%3c %0a%3c ™ In B. ix. c. 72. As Ajasson remarks, it is quite possible that the %0a%3c sting of the Pastinaca might penetrate to the heart of a young tree, and %0a%3c so kill it ; but that is no proof of its being poisonous. See also B ix cc %0a%3c 40, 67. %0a%3c %0a%3c 79 Or Mustek, the sea-weasel, mentioned in B. ix. c. 29 and in c 37 %0a%3c of the present Book. See also Note 12 to B. ix. c. '29. 'Ajasson is of %0a%3c opinion that under the names of " Galeos " and " Mustek," the ancients %0a%3c confounded the Squalus galeus and the Squalus mustelus of Linnseus %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 13.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c AMPHIBIOUS ANIMALS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 13 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c though it attacks other marine animals as well, manifests an %0a%3c enmity to the pastinaca in particular, just as on dry land the %0a%3c weasel does to serpents ; with such avidity does it go in pur- %0a%3c suit of what is poisonous even ! Persons stung by the pas- %0a%3c tinaca find a remedy in the flesh of the galeos, as also in that %0a%3c of the sur-mullet and the vegetable production known as %0a%3c laser. 80 %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 13. (3).— AMPHIBIOUS ANIMALS. CASTOBETJM SIXTY-SIX %0a%3c EEMEDIES AND OBSERVATIONS. %0a%3c %0a%3c The might of Nature, too, is equally conspicuous in the %0a%3c animals which live upon dry land as well ; 81 the beaver, for %0a%3c instance, more generally known as " castor," and the testes 82 of %0a%3c which are called in medicine " castorea." Sextius, a most %0a%3c careful enquirer into the nature and history of medicinal sub- %0a%3c stances, assures us that it is not the truth that this animal, %0a%3c when on the point of being taken, bites off its testes : he in- %0a%3c forms us, also, that these substances are small, tightly knit, %0a%3c and attached to the back-bone, and that it is impossible to %0a%3c remove them without taking the animal's life. We learn from %0a%3c him that there is a mode of adulterating them by substituting %0a%3c the kidneys of the beaver, which are of considerable size, %0a%3c whereas the genuine testes are found to be extremely diminu- %0a%3c tive : in addition to which, he says that they must not be taken %0a%3c to be bladders, as they are two in number, a provision not to be %0a%3c found in any animal. Within these pouches, 83 he says, there %0a%3c is a liquid found, which is preserved by being put in salt ; the %0a%3c genuine castoreum being easily known from the false, by the %0a%3c fact of its being contained in two pouches, attached by a single %0a%3c ligament. The genuine article, he says, is sometimes fraudu- %0a%3c lently sophisticated by the admixture of gum and blood, or %0a%3c else hammoniacum : 84 as the pouches, in fact, ought to be of %0a%3c %0a%3c 80 See B. xix. c. 15, and B. xxii. c. 49. %0a%3c %0a%3c 81 As water, and are consequently amphibious. %0a%3c %0a%3c 82 The Castoreum of the ancients, the " castor" of our Materia Medica, %0a%3c is not in reality produced from the testes of the beaver, as was supposed %0a%3c by the ancients, but from two oral pouches situate near the anus of the %0a%3c animal of either sex. There are four of these pouches in all, two con- %0a%3c taining a species of fat, and two larger ones including in their membranous %0a%3c cells a viscous fetid substance, which forms the castor of medicine. It is %0a%3c considered to be an antispasmodic. %0a%3c %0a%3c 8:5 " Folliculos." A very appropriate term, as Ajasson remarks. %0a%3c 84 See B. xii. c. 49, and B. xxxiv. c. 14. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 14 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c plint's natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXXII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c the same colour as this last, covered with thin coats full of a %0a%3c liquid of the consistency of honey mixed with wax, possessed %0a%3c of a fetid smell, of a bitter, acrid taste, and friable to the %0a%3c touch. %0a%3c %0a%3c The most efficacious castoreum is that which comes from %0a%3c Pontus and Galatia, the next best being the produce of Africa. %0a%3c When inhaled, it acts as a sternutatory. Mixed with oil of %0a%3c roses and peucedanum, 85 and applied to the head, it is produc- %0a%3c tive of narcotic effects — a result which is equally produced by %0a%3c taking it in water ; for which reason it is employed in the %0a%3c treatment of phrenitis. Used as a fumigation, it acts as an %0a%3c excitant upon patients suffering from lethargy : and similarly %0a%3c employed, or used in the form of a suppository, it dispels hy- %0a%3c sterical* 6 suffocations. It acts also as an emmenagogue and as %0a%3c an expellent of the afterbirth, being taken by the patient, in %0a%3c doses of two drachmae, with pennyroyal, 87 in water. It is em- %0a%3c ployed also for the cure of vertigo, opisthotony, fits of trem- %0a%3c bling, spasms, affections of the sinews, sciatica, stomachic %0a%3c complaints, and paralysis, the patient either being rubbed with %0a%3c it all over, or else taking it as an electuary, bruised and incor- %0a%3c porated with seed of vitex, 88 vinegar, and oil of roses, to the %0a%3c consistency of honey. In the last form, too, it is taken for the %0a%3c cure of epilepsy, and in a potion, for the purpose of dispelling %0a%3c flatulency and gripings in the bowels, and for counteracting the %0a%3c effects of poison. %0a%3c %0a%3c When taken as a potion, the only difference is in the mode %0a%3c of mixing it, according to the poison that it is intended to %0a%3c neutralize ; thus, for example, when it is taken for the sting %0a%3c of the scorpion, wine is used as the medium ; and when for %0a%3c injuries inflicted by spiders or by the phalangium, 89 honied %0a%3c wine where it is intended to be brought up again, and rue %0a%3c where it is desirable that it should remain upon the stomach. %0a%3c For injuries inflicted by the chalcis, 90 it is taken with myrtle %0a%3c wine ; for the sting of the cerastes 91 or prester 92 with panax 93 or %0a%3c %0a%3c 83 See B. xxv. c. 70. %0a%3c %0a%3c 66 Castor is still given to females to inhale, when suffering from hysteria %0a%3c %0a%3c 87 See B. xx. c. 54. 8b s fce B. xxiv. c. 38. %0a%3c %0a%3c 89 See B. viii. c. 41, B. x. c. 95, and B. xi. cc 24 28 %0a%3c %0a%3c » See B. xxix. c 32 h See B. viii. c. 35,' and B. xvi, c. 80. %0a%3c %0a%3c I," f ee sx - c> L 1 ; B> XXU - C " 13 ; B - xxlii - c - 23 > & xxiv. c. 73. %0a%3c 93 See B. xii. c. 57. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 14.J %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE TORTOISE. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 15 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c rue in -wine ; and for those of other serpents, with wine only. %0a%3c In all these cases two drachmas of castoreum is the proper %0a%3c dose, to one of the other ingredients respectively. It is par- %0a%3c ticularly useful, also, in combination with vinegar, in cases %0a%3c where viscus 94 has been taken internally, and, with milk or %0a%3c water, as a neutralizer of aconite: as an antidote to white %0a%3c hellebore it is taken with hydromel and nitre. 95 It is cura- %0a%3c tive, also, of tooth-ache, for which purpose it is beaten up %0a%3c with oil and injected into the ear, on the side affected. For %0a%3c the cure of ear-ache, the best plan is to mix it with meco- %0a%3c nium. 96 Applied with Attic honey in the form of an ointment, %0a%3c it improves the eyesight, and taken with vinegar it arrests %0a%3c hiccup. %0a%3c %0a%3c The urine, too, of the beaver, is a neutralizer of poisons, %0a%3c and for this reason is used as an ingredient in antidotes. The %0a%3c best way of keeping it, some think, is in the bladder of the %0a%3c animal. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 14 (4.) — THE TORTOISE : SIXTV-SIX REMEDIES ANI> OBSER- %0a%3c VATIONS. %0a%3c %0a%3c The tortoise, 97 too, is an animal that is equally amphibious %0a%3c with the beaver, and possessed of medicinal properties as %0a%3c strongly developed ; in addition to which, it claims an equal %0a%3c degree of notice for the high price which luxury sets upon its %0a%3c shell, 98 and the singularity of its conformation. Of tortoises, %0a%3c there are various kinds, land tortoises, 99 sea tortoises, 1 tortoises 2 %0a%3c which live in muddy waters, and tortoises 2 which live in fresh ; %0a%3c these last being known to some Greek authors by the name of %0a%3c " emydes." The flesh of the land- tortoise is employed for %0a%3c fumigations more particularly, and we find it asserted that it %0a%3c is highly salutary for repelling the malpractices of magic, and for %0a%3c %0a%3c 91 Or Mistletoe ; see B. xvi. c. 92. %0a%3c %0a%3c 95 As to tbe identity of the "nitrum" of the ancients, see B. xxxi. %0a%3c c. 46 and the Notes. %0a%3c %0a%3c 96 See B. xx. c. 76. %0a%3c %0a%3c 97 Under the head of " testudines," he includes the tortoises, terra- %0a%3c penes, and turtles, which form an order of reptiles, known in Natural %0a%3c History as Chelonia, and characterised by the body being enclosed be- %0a%3c tween a double shield or shell, out of which protrude the head, tail, and %0a%3c four extremities. %0a%3c %0a%3c 98 See B. ix. cc. 11, 12. 99 Our tortoises so called. %0a%3c %0a%3c 1 Our Chelonides, or turtles. %0a%3c %0a%3c 2 The Emydes and Trionyches of Modern Natural History. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 16 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c flint's NATURAL HISTOEY. [Book XXXII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c neutralizing poisons. These tortoises are found in the greatest %0a%3c numbers in Africa ; where the head and feet being first cut off, %0a%3c it is said, they are given to persons by way of antidote. %0a%3c Eaten, too, in a broth made from them, they are thought to %0a%3c disperse scrofula, diminish the volume of the spleen, and effect %0a%3c the cure of epilepsy. The blood of the land-tortoise improves %0a%3c the eyesight, and removes cataract : it is kept also, made up %0a%3c with meal into pills, which are given with wine when neces- %0a%3c sary, to neutralize the poison of all kinds of serpents, frogs, %0a%3c spiders, and similar venomous Animals. It is found a useful %0a%3c plan, too, in cases of glaucoma, to anoint the eyes with gall of %0a%3c tortoises, mixed with Attic honey, and, for the cure of injuries %0a%3c inflicted by scorpions, to drop the gall into the wound. %0a%3c %0a%3c Ashes of tortoiseshell, kneaded up with wine and oil, are %0a%3c used for the cure of chaps upon the feet, and of ulcerations. %0a%3c The shavings of the surface of the shell, administered in drink, %0a%3c act as an antaphrodisiac : a thing that is the more surprising, %0a%3c from the fact that a powder prepared from the whole of the shell %0a%3c has the reputation of being a strong aphrodisiac. As to the urine %0a%3c of the land-tortoise, I do not think that it can be obtained %0a%3c otherwise than by opening it and taking out the bladder ; this %0a%3c being one of those substances to which the adepts in magic %0a%3c attribute such marvellous properties. For the sting of the %0a%3c asp, they say, it is wonderfully effectual ; and even more 60, %0a%3c if bugs are mixed with it. The eggs of the tortoise, hardened %0a%3c by keeping, are applied to scrofulous sores and ulcers arising %0a%3c from burns or cold : they are taken also for pains in the %0a%3c stomach. %0a%3c %0a%3c The flesh of the sea-tortoise, 3 mixed with that of frogs, is %0a%3c an excellent remedy for injuries caused by the salamander; 4 %0a%3c indeed there is nothing that is a better neutralizer of the secre- %0a%3c tions of the salamander than the sea-tortoise. The blood of %0a%3c this animal reproduces the hair when lost through alopecy, %0a%3c and is curative of porrigo and all kinds of ulcerations of the %0a%3c head ; the proper method of using it being to let it dry, and %0a%3c then gently wash it off. For the cure of ear-ache, this blood %0a%3c is injected with woman's milk, and for epilepsy it is eaten %0a%3c with fine wheaten flour, three heminae of the blood being %0a%3c mixed with one hemina of vinegar. It is prescribed also for %0a%3c the cure of asthma ; but in this cas%3ce in combination with one %0a%3c 3 Or turtle. * See B. x. c. 86. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 14.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE TORTOISE. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 17 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c hemina of wine. Sometimes, too, it is taken by asthmatic %0a%3c patients, with barley-meal and vinegar, in pieces about the %0a%3c size of a bean ; one of these pieces being taken each morn- %0a%3c ing and evening at first, but after some days, two in the %0a%3c evening. In cases of epilepsy, the mouth of the patient %0a%3c is opened and this blood introduced. For spasmodic affections, %0a%3c when not of a violent nature, it is injected, in combination with %0a%3c castoreum, as a clyster. If a person rinses his teeth three %0a%3c times a year with blood of tortoises, he will be always ex- %0a%3c empt from tooth-ache. This blood is also a cure for asthmatic %0a%3c affections, and for the malady called " orthopnoea," being admi- %0a%3c nistered for these purposes in polenta. %0a%3c %0a%3c The gall of the tortoise improves the eye-sight, effaces scars, %0a%3c and cures affections of the tonsillary glands, quinsy, and all %0a%3c kinds of diseases of the mouth, cancers of that part more par- %0a%3c ticularly, as well as cancer of the testes. Applied to the nos- %0a%3c trils it dispels epilepsy, and sets the patient on his feet : %0a%3c incorporated in vinegar with the slough of a snake, it is a %0a%3c sovereign remedy for purulent di