ortoise, which frequents rivers. %0a%3c When used for its remedial properties, the shell of the animal %0a%3c is removed, and the fat separated from the flesh and beaten up %0a%3c with the plant aizoiim, 7 in combination with unguent and lily %0a%3c seed : a preparation highly effectual, it is said, for the cure of %0a%3c quartan fevers, the patient being rubbed with it all over, the %0a%3c head excepted, just before the paroxysms come on, and then %0a%3c well wrapped up and made to drink hot water. It is stated %0a%3c also, that to obtain as much fat as possible, the tortoise should %0a%3c be taken on the fifteenth day of the moon, the patient being %0a%3c anointed on the sixteenth. The blood of this tortoise, dropt, %0a%3c by way of embrocation, upon the region of the brain, allays %0a%3c head-ache ; it is curative also of scrofulous sores. Some per- %0a%3c sons recommend that the tortoise should be laid 8 upon its back %0a%3c and its head cut off with a copper knife, the blood being re- %0a%3c ceived in a new earthen vessel ; and they assure us that the %0a%3c blood of any kind of tortoise, when thus obtained, will be an %0a%3c excellent liniment for the cure of erysipelas, running ulcers %0a%3c upon the head, and warts. Upon the same authority, too, we %0a%3c are assured that the dung of any kind of tortoise is good for %0a%3c the removal of inflammatory tumours. Incredible also as %0a%3c the statement is, we find it asserted by some, that ships 9 make %0a%3c way more slowly when they have the right foot of a tortoise %0a%3c on board. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 15. — REMEDIES DERIVED FROM THE AQUATIC ANIMALS, %0a%3c CLASSIFIED ACCORDING TO THE RESPECTIVE DISEASES. %0a%3c %0a%3c We will now proceed to classify the various remedies de- %0a%3c rived from the aquatic animals, according to the several dis- %0a%3c eases ; not that we are by any means unaware that an expo- %0a%3c sition of all the properties of each animal at once, would be %0a%3c more to the reader's taste, 