a%3c cadmia, 3 one drachma of each, it disperses webs which im- %0a%3c pede the eyesight, as also albugo in the eyes of cattle. They %0a%3c say, too, that if the eyelids are rubbed with the small bone 4 %0a%3c taken from this fish, a perfect cure will be experienced. %0a%3c %0a%3c Sea-urchins, applied with vinegar, cause epinyctis to dis- %0a%3c appear. According to what the magicians say, they should be %0a%3c burnt with vipers' skins and frogs, and the ashes sprinkled in %0a%3c the drink ; a great improvement of the eyesight being gua- %0a%3c ranteed as the sure result. %0a%3c %0a%3c "Ichthyocolla" 6 is the name given to a fish with a glutinous %0a%3c Bkin ; the glue made from which is also known by the same %0a%3c name, and is highly useful for the removal of epinyctis. %0a%3c Some persons, however, assert that it is from the belly of the %0a%3c fish, and not the skin — as in the case of bull glue — that the %0a%3c ichthyocolla is prepared. That of Pontus 6 is highly esteemed : %0a%3c it is white, free from veins or scales, and dissolves with the %0a%3c greatest rapidity. The proper way of using it, is to cut it %0a%3c into small pieces, and then to leave it to soak in water or %0a%3c vinegar a night and a day, after which it should be pounded %0a%3c %0a%3c 2 Cortex. 3 See B. xxxiv. cc. 22, 23. 4 " Ossiculo." %0a%3c %0a%3c 5 Literally, " fish-glue." We can hardly believe Pliny that any fish %0a%3c was known by this name. Hardouin takes the fish here spoken of to be %0a%3c identical with that mentioned in B. ix. c. 17, as being caught in the %0a%3c Borysthene, and destitute of bones. It is most probable, however, that %0a%3c the "ichthyocolla" of the ancients, or "fish-glue," was the same as our %0a%3c isinglass, and that it was prepared from the entrails of various fish, the %0a%3c ■tnrgeon more particularly, the Acipenser huso of Linnaeus. %0a%3c %0a%3c 6 The best isinglass still comes from Russia. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 32 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLINY