llionymus, 16 injected into the ears with oil of roses, or else %0a%3c eastoreum, 16 used with poppy-juice. There are certain animals %0a%3c too, known as "sea-lice," 17 which are recommended as an %0a%3c injection for the ears, beaten up with vinegar. Wool, too, %0a%3c that has been dyed with the juice of the murex, employed %0a%3c by itself, is highly useful for this purpose ; some persons, %0a%3c however moisten it with vinegar and nitre. 18 %0a%3c %0a%3c Others, again, more particularly recommend for all affections %0a%3c of the ears one cyathus of the best garum, 19 with one cyathus %0a%3c and a half of honey, and one cyathus of vinegar, the whole %0a%3c gently boiled in a new pot over a slow fire, and skimmed with %0a%3c a feather every now and then : when it has become wholly %0a%3c free from scum, it is injected lukewarm into the ears. In %0a%3c cases where the ears are swollen, the same authorities recom- %0a%3c mend that the swellings should be first reduced with juice of %0a%3c coriander. The fat of frogs, injected into the ears, instantly %0a%3c removes all pains in these organs. The juice of river-crabs, %0a%3c kneaded up with barley-meal, is a most effectual remedy for %0a%3c wounds in the ears. Shells of the murex, reduced to ashes, %0a%3c %0a%3c 12 Another reading is " ttenia," a fish mentioned by Epicbarmus, %0a%3c Athenaeus informs us, and considered by Ajasson to be probably identical %0a%3c with the Cepola rubescens, or Cepola taenia of Linnaeus. %0a%3c %0a%3c 13 The same as the Batis of the Greeks, Hardouin thinks, the Raia %0a%3c batis, a kind of skate. %0a%3c %0a%3c 14 See B. ix. c. 28. 15 See the preceding Chapter. %0a%3c 16 See c. 13 of the present Book. 17 See B. ix. c. 71. %0a%3c %0a%3c 18 As to " nitrum," see B. xxxi. c. 46. %0a%3c %0a%3c 19 See B. xxxi. c. 43. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c VOL. VI. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c D %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 34 flint's NATURAL HISTORY. [Book XXXII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c and applied with