ooth %0a%3c only. Ashes, too, of burnt crabs are used for this purpose; %0a%3c and the murex, reduced to ashes, makes an excellent den- %0a%3c tifrice. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 27. — REMEDIES FOE. LICHENS, AND FOE SPOTS UPON THE %0a%3c FACE. THE DOIPHIN : NINE REMEDIES. COLUTHIA OR CORT- %0a%3c PHIA : THREE REMEDIES. HALCYONEDM : SEVEN REMEDIES. %0a%3c THE TUNNY : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Lichens and leprous spots are removed by applying the fat %0a%3c of the sea-calf, 29 ashes of the msena 30 in combination with three %0a%3c oboli of honey, liver of the pastinaca 31 boiled in oil, or ashes %0a%3c of the dolphin or hippocampus 32 mixed with water. After the %0a%3c parts have been duly excoriated, a cicatrizing treatment ought %0a%3c to be pursued. Some persons bake dolphin's liver in an %0a%3c earthen vessel, till a grease flows therefrom like oil 33 in ap- %0a%3c %0a%3c 2fl See B. ix. cc. 40, 67. 27 " Cetum." See B. ix. cc. 40, 74. %0a%3c %0a%3c 28 Ajasson is of opinion that here and in c. 19 Pliny has mistaken the %0a%3c otter for a serpent, the mammiferae only having eye or canine teeth. %0a%3c Aristotle, Hist. Anim. B. i. c. i., calls the otter by the name of "Enhy- %0a%3c dris." See B. xxx. c. 8, where Pliny speaks of the "Enhydris" as a %0a%3c " male white serpent." 29 Or seal. See B. ix. c. 15. %0a%3c %0a%3c 30 See B. ix. c. 42. Holland calls the raaena the " cackerel." %0a%3c %0a%3c 31 Or sting-ray. « g ee j X- C- i, %0a%3c %0a%3c 33 Much like the cod-liver oil, held in such high repute at the present day. %0a%3c %0a%3c D 2 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c i*6 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLINY'S NATURAL HISTOKT. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXXII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pearance : this they use by way of ointment for these dis- %0a%3c eases. %0a%3c %0a%3c Burnt shells of the murex or purple, applied with honey, %0a%3c have a detergent effect upon spots on the face in females: %0a%3c used as an application for seven consecutive days, a fomenta- %0a%3c tion made of white of eggs being substituted on the eighth, %0a%3c they efface wrinkles, and plump out the skin. To the genus %0a%3c " murex" belong the shell-fish known by the Greeks as " co- %0a%3c luthia" or " coryphia," equally turbinated, but considerably %0a%3c smaller : for all the above purposes they are still more effica- %0a%3c cious, and the use of them tends to preserve the sweetness of %0a%3c the breath. Fish-glue 34 effaces wrinkles and plumps out the skin; %0a%3c being boiled for the purpose in water some four hours, and then %0a%3c pounded and kneaded up till it attains a thin consistency, like %0a%3c that of honey. After being thus prepared, it is put by in a new %0a%3c vessel for keeping ; and, when wanted for use, is mixed, in %0a%3c the proportion of four drachmae, with two drachma? of sulphur, %0a%3c two of alkanet, and eight of litharge ; the whole beiDg %0a%3c sprinkled with water and beaten up together. The prepara- %0a%3c tion is then applied to the face, and is washed off at the end %0a%3c of four hours. For the cure of freckles and other affections %0a%3c of the face, calcined bones of cuttle-fish are also used ; an %0a%3c application which is equally good for the removal of fleshy %0a%3c excrescences and the dispersion of running sores. %0a%3c %0a%3c (8.) For the cure of itch-scab, a frog is boiled in five semisex- %0a%3c tarii of sea-water, the decoction being reduced to the consistency %0a%3c of honey. There is a sea production called " halcyon eum," com- %0a%3c posed, as some think, of the nests 35 of the birds known as the %0a%3c "halcyon" 36 and "ceyx," or, according to others, of the con- %0a%3c cretion of sea-foam, or of some slime of the sea, or a certain %0a%3c lanuginous inflorescence thrown up by it. Of this halcyoneum %0a%3c there are four different kinds ; the first, of an ashy colour, of a %0a%3c compact substance, and possessed of a pungent odour ; the %0a%3c second, soft, of a milder nature, and with a smell almost iden- %0a%3c %0a%3c 34 " Icthyocolla." See Chapter 24 of the present Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c 33 Of course this assertion as to the nest of the kingfisher is altogether %0a%3c fahulous, and the sea-productions here described by Pliny were lon» con- %0a%3c sidered, though destitute of leaves, flowers, and fruit, to belong to the %0a%3c vegetable kingdom. Peyssonnel, however, made the discovery that they %0a%3c belong to the animal kingdom, and that they owe their origin to a species %0a%3c of polyp. %0a%3c %0a%3c 3 » Or kingfisher. See B. x. c. 47. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 28.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDIES FOR SCROFULA, %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 37 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c tical with that of sea-weed ; the third, whiter, and with a %0a%3c variegated surface ; the fourth, more like pumice in appear- %0a%3c ance, and closely resembling rotten sponge. The best of all is %0a%3c that which nearty borders upon a purple hue, and is known as %0a%3c the " Milesian" kind : the whiter it is, the less highly it is %0a%3c esteemed. %0a%3c %0a%3c The properties of halcyoneum are ulcerative and detergent : %0a%3c when required for use, it is parched and applied without oil . %0a%3c It is quite marvellous how efficiently it removes leprous sores, %0a%3c lichens, and freckles, used in combination with lupines and %0a%3c two oboli of sulphur. It is employed, also, for the removal %0a%3c of marks upon the eyes. 37 Andreas 38 has recommended for the %0a%3c cure of leprosy ashes of burnt crabs, with oil ; and Attalus, 39 %0a%3c fresh fat of tunny. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 28. — REMEDIES FOR SCROFULA, IMPOSTHTTMES OF THE PA- %0a%3c ROTID GLANDS, aUINSY, AND DISEASES OF THE FAUCES. THE %0a%3c JUBNA : THIRTEEN REMEDIES. THE SEA-SCOLOPENDRA ! TWO %0a%3c REMEDIES. THE SAUHUS : ONE REMEDY. SHELL-FISH : ONE %0a%3c REMEDY. THE SILURUS : FIFTEEN REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Ulcerations of the mouth are cured by an application ^ of %0a%3c brine in which maense 40 have been pickled, in combination with %0a%3c calcined heads of the fish, and honey. Tor the cure of scro- %0a%3c fula, it is a good plan to prick the sores with the small bone %0a%3c that is found in the tail of the fish known as the sea-frog ; 41 %0a%3c care being taken to avoid making a wound, and to repeat the %0a%3c operation daily, until a perfect cure is effected. The same %0a%3c property, too, belongs to the sting of the pastinaca, and to the %0a%3c sea-hare, applied topically to the sores : but in both cases due %0a%3c care must be taken to remove them in an instant. Shells of %0a%3c sea-urchins are bruised, also, and applied with vinegar ; shells %0a%3c also of sea-scolopendrae, 42 applied with honey ; and river-crabs %0a%3c pounded or calcined, and applied with honey. Bones, too, of %0a%3c the ssepia, triturated and applied with stale axle-grease, are %0a%3c marvellously useful for this purpose. %0a%3c %0a%3c S7 " Oculorum cicatrices." 38 See end of B. xx. %0a%3c %0a%3c 39 See end of B. via. 40 See B. ix. c. 42. %0a%3c %0a%3c 41 See B. ix. cc. 40, 67. The Bamberg MS. has here " rhine " (the %0a%3c tish again mentioned in Chapter 53 of this Book) instead of "rana; ' a %0a%3c reading which Sillig rejects. Hardouin conjectures that "raia" is the %0a%3c correct reading, the sea-frog having no sting or stickle in the tail. %0a%3c %0a%3c ** See B. ix. c. 67. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 38 flint's NATURAL HISTOBT. [Book XXXII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c This last preparation is used, also, for the cure of lmpost- %0a%3c humes of the parotid glands ; a purpose for which the liver %0a%3c of the sea-fish known as the " saurus" 43 is employed. Nay, %0a%3c even more than this, fragments of earthen vessels in which %0a%3c salt fish have been kept are pounded with stale axle-grease, %0a%3c and applied to scrofulous sores and imposthumes of the parotid %0a%3c glands ; as also calcined murex, incorporated with oil. Stiffness %0a%3c in the neck is allayed by taking what are known as sea-lice, 43 ' %0a%3c in