r whether he means the gum ammoniac of B. xii. c. 49 %0a%3c and B. xxiv. c. 14, or the sal ammoniac of 15. xxxi. c. 39. %0a%3c %0a%3c 48 "Saliva." See the recipe of Sallustius Dionysius in Chapter 26 of %0a%3c this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 31. J REMEDIES FOB, DISEASES OF THE BOWELS. 39 %0a%3c %0a%3c purpose. There is a small frog, 49 also, which ascends trees, and %0a%3c croaks aloud there : if a persou suffering from cough spits into %0a%3c its mouth and then lets it go, he will experience a cure, it is said. %0a%3c For cough attended with spitting of blood, it is recommended %0a%3c to beat up the raw flesh of a snail, and to drink it in hot water. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 30. (9.) REMEDIES FOR FAINS IN THE LIVER AND SIDE. %0a%3c %0a%3c THE ELONGATED CONCH : SIX REMEDIES. THE TETHEA : FIVE %0a%3c REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c For pains in the liver, a sea-scorpion is killed in wine, and %0a%3c the liquid is taken. The meat, too, of the elongated conch 50 is %0a%3c taken with honied wine and water, in equal quantities, or, if %0a%3c there are symptoms of fever, with hyd'romel. Pains in the %0a%3c side are assuaged by taking the flesh of the hippocampus, 61 %0a%3c grilled, or else the tethea, 61 * very similar to the oyster, with %0a%3c the ordinary food. For sciatica, the pickle of the silurus is %0a%3c injected, by way of clyster. The flesh of conchs, too, is pre- %0a%3c scribed, for fifteen days, in doses of three oboli soaked in two %0a%3c sextarii of wine. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 31. — REMEDIES FOR DISEASES OF THE BOWELS. SEA-WORT : %0a%3c ONE REMEDY. THE MYAX : TWENTY-FIVE REMEDIES. THE MITU- %0a%3c LUS ! EIGHT REMEDIES. TELOEIDES : ONE REMEDY. SEK1PHUM: %0a%3c TWO REMEDIES. THE ERYTHINITS : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The silurus, 52 taken in its broth, or the torpedo, 53 used as %0a%3c food, acts as a laxative upon the bowels. There is a sea-wort, 51 %0a%3c also, similar in appearance to the cultivated cabbage : it is %0a%3c injurious to the' stomach, but acts most efficiently as a purga- %0a%3c tive, requiring to be cooked with fat meat for the purpose, in %0a%3c consequence of its extreme acridity. The broth, too, of all %0a%3c boiled fish is good for this purpose ; it acting, also, as a strong %0a%3c diuretic, taken with wine more particularly. The best kind %0a%3c of all is that prepared from the sea-scorpion, the iulis, 55 and %0a%3c %0a%3c 49 The Dryophites of Rondelet, Dalechamps says. %0a%3c %0a%3c 60 Identical with the Strombus of cc. 39, 46, and 53 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c " See B. ix. c. 1. %0a%3c %0a%3c «• Littre remarks that Pliny here seems to speak of the "Tethea" as %0a%3c a mollusk ; whereas in c. 31, from his expression " Fungorum venus %0a%3c generis quam piscium," he would appear to be describing a zoophyte. %0a%3c %0a%3c " See B. ix. cc. 17, 25, 75. %0a%3c %0a%3c « See B. ix. cc. 24, 48, 67, 74, 75. 54 See B. xx. c. 38. %0a%3c %0a%3c 85 A rock fish, according to Atheneeus, B. vii. Eondelet, B. vi. c. 7, %0a%3c identifies it with' the fish, called girdlo by the people of Liguria, the don- %0a%3c sella of other districts. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 40 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliity's natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXXII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c rock-fish in general, as they are destitute of all rankness and %0a%3c are free from fat. The proper way of cooking them is with %0a%3c dill, parsley, coriander, and leeks, with the addition of oil and %0a%3c salt. Stale cybium, 66 too, acts as a purgative, and is particularly %0a%3c useful for carrying on 0 crudities, pituitous humours, and bile. %0a%3c %0a%3c The myax 57 is of a purgative nature, a shell-fish of which %0a%3c we shall take this opportunity of giving the natural his- %0a%3c tory at length. These fish collect together in masses, like the %0a%3c iuurex, 58 and are found in spots covered with sea-weed. They %0a%3c are the finest eating in autumn, and are found in the greatest %0a%3c perfection in places where fresh-water streams discharge them- %0a%3c selves into the sea ; for which reason it is that those of Egypt %0a%3c are held in such high esteem. As the winter advances, they %0a%3c contract a bitter flavour, and assume a reddish hue. The %0a%3c liquor of these fish, it is said, acts as a purgative upon the %0a%3c bowels and bladder, has a detergent effect upon the intestines, %0a%3c acts aperiently upon all the passages, purges the kidneys, and %0a%3c diminishes the blood and adipose secretions. Hence it is that %0a%3c these shell-fish are found of the greatest use for the treatment %0a%3c of dropsy, for the regulation of the catamenia, and for the re- %0a%3c moval of jaundice, all diseases of the joints, and flatulency. %0a%3c They are very good, also, for the reduction of obesity, for %0a%3c diseases of the bile and of the pituitous secretions, for affec- %0a%3c tions of the lungs, liver, and spleen, and for rheumatic de- %0a%3c fluxions. The only inconvenience resulting from them is, that %0a%3c they irritate the throat and impede the articulation. They %0a%3c have, also, a healing effect upon ulcers of a serpiginous nature, %0a%3c or which stand in need of detergents, as also upon carcinoma- %0a%3c tous sores. Calcined, the same way as the murex, and em- %0a%3c ployed with honey, they are curative of bites inflicted either %0a%3c by dogs or human beings, and of leprous spots or freckles. The %0a%3c ashes of them, rinsed, are good for the removal of films upon %0a%3c the eyes, granulations of those organs and indurations of the %0a%3c membrane, as also for diseases of the gums and teeth, and for %0a%3c pituitous eruptions. They serve, also, as an antidote to doryc- %0a%3c nium 59 and to opocarpathon. 60 %0a%3c %0a%3c 56 Sliced tunny. See E. ix. c. 18. %0a%3c %0a%3c 57 A genus which comprises the "myes," mentioned in B. ix. c 56 %0a%3c according to Dalechamps. %0a%3c %0a%3c 515 See B. ix. c. 60. 59 g ee g xxi c 1Q5 %0a%3c %0a%3c 60 See B. xxviii. c. 45, and Chapter 20 of the present Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 31.] EEAIKDIES FOE DISEASES OF THE BOWELS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 41 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c There are two species of this shell-fish, of a degenerate kind : %0a%3c the mitulus, 61 which has a strong flavour, and a saltish taste ; %0a%3c and the myisca, 62 which differs from the former in the roundness %0a%3c of its shell, is somewhat smaller, and is covered with filaments, %0a%3c the shell being thinner, and the meat of a sweeter flavour. The %0a%3c ashes, also, of the mitulus, like those of the murex, are pos- %0a%3c sessed of certain caustic properties, and are very useful for the %0a%3c removal of leprous spots, freckles, and blemishes of the skin. %0a%3c They are rinsed, too, in the same manner as lead, 63 for the %0a%3c removal of swellings of the eyelids, of indurations of the %0a%3c membranes, and of films upon the eyes, as also of sordid ulcers %0a%3c upon other parts of the body, and of pustules upon the head. %0a%3c The meat of them, also, is employed as an application for bites %0a%3c inflicted by dogs. %0a%3c %0a%3c As to pelorides, 64 they act as a gentle laxative upon the %0a%3c bowels, an effect equally produced by castoreum, taken in doses %0a%3c of two drachmae, in hydromel : where, however, a more drastic %0a%3c purgative is recpiired, one drachma of dried garden-cucumber %0a%3c root is added, and two drachmae of aphronitrum. 69 The %0a%3c tethea 66 is good for griping pains in the bowels and for attacks %0a%3c of flatulency : they are generally found adhering to the leaves %0a%3c of marine plants, sucking their nutriment therefrom, and may %0a%3c be rather looked upon as a sort of fungus than as a fish. They %0a%3c are useful, also, for the removal of tenesmus and of diseases of %0a%3c the kidneys. %0a%3c %0a%3c There grows also in the sea a kind of absinthium, known by %0a%3c some persons as " seriphum," 67 and found in the vicinity of %0a%3c Taposiris, 68 in Egypt, more particularly. It is of a more %0a%3c slender form than the land absinthium, acts as a purgative %0a%3c upon the bowels, and effectually removes intestinal worms. %0a%3c The ssepia, too, is a laxative ; for which purpose these fish are %0a%3c %0a%3c 61 Identical with our mussel, probably. %0a%3c %0a%3c 62 Holland identifies this with the cockle, but it is probably a smaller %0a%3c kind of mussel. 63 See B. xxxiv. c. 50. %0a%3c %0a%3c 61 We learn from Chapter 53 of this Book, that one class of the %0a%3c "Cbamae," or gaping cockles, was known as "Pelorides." Horace also %0a%3c mentions them. %0a%3c %0a%3c 65 See B. xxxi. c. 46. %0a%3c %0a%3c 66 See Note 51 above. Sillig would here read " tetheum," apparently, %0a%3c in the singular. ' 67 Described in B. xxvii. c. 29. %0a%3c %0a%3c 6S A city not far from the Canopic branch of the Kile. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 42 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c punt's natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXXII %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c administered 69 with the food, hoiled with a mixture of oil, salt, %0a%3c and meal. Salted mamae, 70 applied with bull's gall to the navel, %0a%3c acts as a purgative upon the bowels. %0a%3c %0a%3c The liquor of fish, boiled in the saucepan with lettuces, dispels %0a%3c tenesmus. River-crabs, 71 beaten up and taken with water, act %0a%3c astringently upon the bowels, and they have a diuretic effect, if %0a%3c taken with white wine. Deprived of the legs, and taken in %0a%3c doses of three oboli with myrrh and iris, one drachma of each, %0a%3c they disperse urinary calculi. For the cure of the iliac pas- %0a%3c sion and of attacks of flatulency, castoreum 72 should be taken, %0a%3c with seed of daucus 73 and of parsley, a pinch in three fingers %0a%3c of each, the whole being mixed with four cyathi of warm %0a%3c honied wine. Griping pains in the bowels should be treated %0a%3c with castoreum and a mixture of dill and wine. The fish %0a%3c called " erythinus," 74 used as food, acts astringently upon the %0a%3c bowels. Dysentery is cured by taking frogs boiled with squills, %0a%3c and prepared in the form of boluses, or else hearts of frogs %0a%3c beaten up with honey, as Niceratus 76 recommends. For the %0a%3c cure of jaundice, salt fish should be taken with pepper, the %0a%3c patient abstaining from all other kinds of meat. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 32. REMEDIES FOE DISEASES OF THE SPLEEN, FOE URI- %0a%3c NARY CALCULI, AND FOE AFFECTIONS OF THE BLADDER. THE %0a%3c SOLE : ONE EEMEDY. THE TURBOT : ONE EEMEDY. THE %0a%3c BLENDIUS : ONE EEMEDY. THE SKA- NETTLE : SEVEN REMEDIES. %0a%3c THE PULMO MAEINUS : SIX EEMEDIES. ONYCHES : FOUR RE- %0a%3c MEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c For the cure of spleen diseases, the fish known as the sole 76 %0a%3c is applied to that part ; the torpedo, 77 also, or else a live tur- %0a%3c bot; 78 it being then set at liberty in the sea. The sea- %0a%3c scorpion, 79 killed in wine, is a cure for diseases of the bladder %0a%3c %0a%3c 69 " Dantur " seems a preferable reading to " datur " %0a%3c %0a%3c 70 See B. ix c. 42. %0a%3c %0a%3c 71 Our crawfish, the Astacus potamobios of Leach. %0a%3c %0a%3c 72 See Chapter 13 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c 73 See B. xix. c. 27, and B. xxv. c. 64. %0a%3c %0a%3c 74 See B. ix. cc. 23, 77. 75 See end of B xxxi %0a%3c %0a%3c 76 See B. ix. cc. 20, 24, 36. %0a%3c %0a%3c 77 See B. ix. cc. 24, 48, 67, 74, 75. %0a%3c %0a%3c « " Rhombus." See B. ix. cc. 20, 36, 67, 79. %0a%3c %0a%3c 79 See Chapters 23, 34, 30 and 53 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 32.] REMEDIES FOB. DISEASES OF THE SPLEEN. 43 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c and for urinary calculi ; the stone, also, that is found in the %0a%3c tail 80 of this last fish, taken in drink, in doses of one obolus ; %0a%3c the liver of the enhydris ; bl and the ashes of the fish called %0a%3c " blendius ; 82 taken with rue. In the head, too, of the fish %0a%3c called " bacchus," 83 there are found certain small stones, as it %0a%3c were : these, taken in water, six in number,