ty drachma?, %0a%3c of litharge forty drachmae, of calcined murex ten drachmae, %0a%3c and of old oil, one semisextarius. Salt fish, boiled and ap- %0a%3c plied by itself, is highly useful for the above purposes. %0a%3c %0a%3c River crabs, bruised and applied, disperse pustules on the %0a%3c generative organs : the same, too, with calcined heads of %0a%3c maenae, 1 or the flesh of that fish, boiled and applied. Heads %0a%3c of salted perch, 2 reduced to ashes, and applied with honey, are %0a%3c equally useful for the purpose ; or else calcined heads of pe- %0a%3c lamides, 3 or skin of the squatina reduced to ashes. 4 It is the %0a%3c skin of this fish that is used, as already 5 stated, for giving a %0a%3c polish to wood ; for the sea even, we find, furnishes its aid to our %0a%3c artificers. For a similar purpose the fishes called " smarides" 6 %0a%3c are applied topically ; as also ashes of the shell of the murex %0a%3c or of the purple, applied with honey ; which last are still more %0a%3c efficacious when the flesh has been burnt with the shell. %0a%3c %0a%3c Salt fish, boiled with honey, is particularly good for the %0a%3c cure of carbuncles upon the generative organs. For relaxation %0a%3c of the testes, the slime 7 of snails is recommended, applied iu %0a%3c the form of a liniment. %0a%3c %0a%3c 98 See B. ix. c. 24. %0a%3c %0a%3c 99 See Chapters 23, 24, 30, 32, and 53 of the present Book. Also B. %0a%3c xx. c. 53. 1 See B. ix. c. 42. %0a%3c %0a%3c 2 " Perca." See B. ix. c. 24. 3 See Note 93 above. %0a%3c 4 See B. ix. c. 14. 6 In B. ix. c. 14. %0a%3c %0a%3c 6 Ajasson remarks that many writers have identified the Smaris with the %0a%3c Sardine or the Anchovy. In his opinion, however, it is neither; but he %0a%3c thinks that under this head were included seven or eight varieties of the %0a%3c Pickerel, the principal of which are, the Sparus smaris of Linnaeus and %0a%3c Lacepede, the Sparus mana of Linnseus, or Sparus mendola of Lac6pede, %0a%3c and the Sparus ha