ady ; 16 %0a%3c due precaution being taken not to apply it dry. %0a%3c %0a%3c Chilblains are cured by applying the pulmo marinus; 17 ashes %0a%3c %0a%3c s See B. ix. c. 1. %0a%3c %0a%3c 9 Literally, the "little serpent." Some think that it is the Ophidium %0a%3c barbatum of Linnaeus. Eondelet identifies it, B. xiv. c. 2, with the small %0a%3c fish called donzella by the people of Montpellier. See c. 31, Note 55. %0a%3c %0a%3c 10 See B. xxx. c. 22. " See B. xiv. c. 8. %0a%3c %0a%3c 18 " Rubetae." See c. 18 of this Book ; also B. viii. c. 48 ; B. xi. cc. 19, %0a%3c 76, 116, and B. xxv. c. 76. %0a%3c %0a%3c 13 See B. ix. c. 72 ; B. xxv. c. 77, and Chapter 3 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c 14 Or seal-skin. See B. viii. c. 49, and B. ix. c. 15, %0a%3c %0a%3c 15 In B. xxvii. c. 33. i« In B. xxvi. c. 66. %0a%3c %0a%3c w Or " sea-lungs." See B. ix. c. 71, B. xviii. c. 5, and Chapters 32, %0a%3c 46, and 52 of the present Book. Ajasson remarks that this is still the %0a%3c common name of many kinds of Medusae. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 33.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDIES FOB, FEVEBS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c a 7 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c of sea-crabs with oil ; river crabs, 18 bruised and burnt to ashes %0a%3c and kneaded up with oil ; or else fat of the silurus. 19 In %0a%3c diseases of the joints, the paroxysms are modified by applying %0a%3c fresh frogs every now and then : some authorities recommend %0a%3c that they should be split asunder before being applied. The %0a%3c liquor from mussels 20 and other shell-fish has a tendency to %0a%3c make flesh. %0a%3c %0a%3c chap. 37. — remedies fob epilepsy. %0a%3c %0a%3c Epileptic patients, as already 21 stated, are recommended to %0a%3c drink the rennet of the sea-calf, 22 mixed with mares' milk or %0a%3c asses' milk, or else with pomegranate juice, or, in some cases, %0a%3c with oxymel : some persons, too, swallow the rennet by itself, %0a%3c in the form of pills. Castoreum 23 is sometimes administered, in %0a%3c