very good for the cure of phthisis. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 40. REMEDIES FOR BURNS AND FOR ERYSIPELAS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Burns are cured by applying ashes of calcined sea-crabs or %0a%3c river-crabs with oil : fish-glue, too, and calcined frogs are %0a%3c used as an application for scalds produced by boiling water. %0a%3c The same treatment also restores the hair, provided the ashes %0a%3c are those of river-crabs : it is generally thought, too, that the %0a%3c preparation should be applied with wax and bears' grease. %0a%3c Ashes, too, of burnt beaver- skin are very useful for these %0a%3c purposes. Live frogs act as a check upon erysipelas, the belly %0a%3c side being applied to the part affected : it is recommended, %0a%3c too, to attach them lengthwise by the hinder legs, so as to %0a%3c render them more beneficial by reason of their increased re- %0a%3c spiration. 38 Heads, too, of salted siluri 39 are reduced to ashes %0a%3c and applied with vinegar. %0a%3c %0a%3c Prurigo and itch-scab, not only in man but in quadrupeds %0a%3c %0a%3c 36 See Chapter 29 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c 37 See Chapters 30 and 31 of the present Book. 37 * See B. xviii. c. 19. %0a%3c %0a%3c 38 " Crebriore anhelitu." 39 See B. ix. cc. 17, 25, 75. %0a%3c VOL. VI. E %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 50 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLINY's NATURAL BISTORT. [Book XXXII- %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c as well, are most efficaciously treated with the liver of the %0a%3c pastinaea 40 boiled in oil. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 41. REMEDIES TOR DISEASES OF THE SINEWS. %0a%3c %0a%3c The exterior callosity with which the flesh of purples is %0a%3c covered, beaten up, unites the sinews, even when they have %0a%3c been severed asunder. It is a good plan, for patients suffering %0a%3c from tetanus, to take sea-calf s rennet in wine, in doses of one %0a%3c obolus, as also fish-glue. 41 Persons affected with fits of trem- %0a%3c bling find much relief from castoreum, 42 provided they arc %0a%3c well anointed with oil. I find it stated that the surmullet, 4 ' %0a%3c used as an article of diet, acts injuriously upon the sinews. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 42. — METHODS OF ARRESTING HAEMORRHAGE AND OF LET- %0a%3c TING ELOOD. THE POLYP : ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c Fish, used as. an aliment, it is generally thought, make %0a%3c blood. The polyp, 44 bruised and applied, arrests haemorrhage, %0a%3c it is thought: in addition to which we find stated the follow- %0a%3c ing particulars respecting it — that of itself it emits a sort of %0a%3c brine, in consequence of which, there is no necessity to use %0a%3c any in cooking it — that it should always be sliced with a reed %0a%3c — "and that it is spoilt by using an iron knife, becoming tainted %0a%3c thereby, owing to the antipathy 45 which naturally exists %0a%3c [between it and iron]. For the purpose also of arresting %0a%3c heemorrhage, ashes of burnt frogs are applied topically, or else %0a%3c the dried blood of those animals. Some authorities recom- %0a%3c mend the frog to be used, that is known by the Greeks as %0a%3c " calamites," 46 from the fact that it lives among reeds 47 and %0a%3c shrubs ; it is the smallest and greenest of all the frogs, and %0a%3c either the blood or the ashes of it are recommended to be em- %0a%3c ployed. Others, again, prescribe, in cases of bleeding at the %0a%3c nostrils, an injection of the ashes of young water-frogs, in the %0a%3c tadpole state, calcined in a new earthen vessel. %0a%3c %0a%3c io Or sting-ray. See B. ix. cc. 37, 40, 67, 72. %0a%3c %0a%3c 41 Ichthyocolla. See Chapter 24 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c 42 See Chapter 13 of this Book. « See B. ix. c. 30. %0a%3c « See B. ix. c. 46. %0a%3c %0a%3c *• This seems to be the meaning of " natura dissidente," if it is the %0a%3c correct reading. That, however, suggested by Dalechamps would seem %0a%3c to be preferable, " natura retinente,"— " it being the nature of its flesh to %0a%3c cling to the knife." %0a%3c %0a%3c « See Chapter 24 of this Book. « " Calami." %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 43.] EXTRACTION OF FOREIGN BODIES FROM FLESH. 51 %0a%3c %0a%3c On the other hand, again, in cases where it is required to %0a%3c let blood, the kind of leech is used which is known among %0a%3c us by the name of " sanguisuga. 48 " Indeed, the action of %0a%3c these leeches is looked upon as pretty much the same as that %0a%3c of the cupping-glasses 49 used in medicine, their effect being to %0a%3c relieve the body of superfluous blood, and to open the pores of %0a%3c the skin. Still, however, there is this inconvenience attend- %0a%3c ing them — when they have been once applied, they create a %0a%3c necessity 60 for having recourse to the same treatment at about %0a%3c the same period in every succeeding year. Many physicians %0a%3c have been of opinion also, that leeches may be successfully ap- %0a%3c plied in cases of gout. When gorged, they fall off in conse- %0a%3c quence of losing their hold through the weight of the blood, %0a%3c but if not, they must be sprinkled with salt 81 for the purpose. %0a%3c %0a%3c Leeches are apt, however, to leave their heads buried in the %0a%3c flesh ; the consequence of which is an incurable wound, which %0a%3c has caused death in many cases, that of Messalinus, 52 for ex- %0a%3c ample, a patrician of consular rank, after an application of %0a%3c leeches to his knee. When this is the case, that which was %0a%3c intended as a remedy is turned into an active poison ; 53 a result %0a%3c which is to be apprehended in using the red leeches more %0a%3c particularly. Hence it is that when these last are employed, %0a%3c it is the practice to snip them with a pair of scissors while %0a%3c sucking ; the consequence of which is, that the blood oozes %0a%3c forth, through a siphon, as it were, and the head, gradually %0a%3c contracting as the animal dies, is not left behind in the wound. %0a%3c There is a natural antipathy 54 existing between leeches and %0a%3c bugs, and hence it is that the latter are killed by the